<HEADLINE> French Troops Evacuate Expatriates from Central African </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, June 25 (Xinhua) -- French troops stationed in the
Central African Republic's capital, Bangui, evacuated 28 French
expatriates, mostly children, on Tuesday to neighboring Gabon.
</P>
<P>
The French forces stepped in after a scheduled Air France
flight was cancelled and took the French nationals to Libreville,
French Foreign Ministry spokesman Jacques Rummelhardt said today.
</P>
<P>
He also said that the French community in Bangui remained
calm under the difficult circumstances.
</P>
<P>
Backed by French helicopters, African soldiers serving in the
Inter-African Mission of Supervision of the Bangui Accords (MISAB)
shelled rebel positions in Bangui on Tuesday, forcing thousands of
people to flee.
</P>
<P>
Bangui is in the grip of its third rebellion within a year by
soldiers opposing President Ange-Felix Patasse.
</P>
<P>
France has deployed an extra 1,600 soldiers in the Central
African Republic under a defense accord to assure the security of
European citizens and to keep President Ange-Felix Patasse in
power. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
