<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-25 15:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Owner of Collapsed Cairo Building Imprisoned </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 25 (Xinhua) -- The Egyptian High Security Court
today meted out a seven-year prison term for the owner of a
building that crumbled in a Cairo suburb last year in the
country's worst tragedy of the type.
</P>
<P>
Raouf Wissa Ibrahim, 60, was convicted of manslaughter for
illegally heightening the eight-story building that fell down
under its added weight.
</P>
<P>
Altogether 64 were killed after the ill-fated building caved in
like the folds of an accordion on its occupants on October 28.
</P>
<P>
Two engineers in charge of constructing the 25-year-old
building in Heliopolis district were sentenced to three years in
prison, with a fine of 325,396 Egyptian pounds (95,000
U.S. dollars) for negligence.
</P>
<P>
Egypt, where sloppy building work and adding extra floors are
common practices, has since toughened penalties on landlords who
cause death or injury by breaking building regulations.
</P>
<P>
In a decree issued last November, Prime Minister Kamal Ganzouri
set a minimum of five years in jail for anyone caught constructing
or renovating a building without a license.
</P>
<P>
If anyone is killed or if three people are injured when an
illegal building collapses, the perpetrators face up to 10 years
in jail with hard labor, the decree said.


25/06/97 15:51 GMT

=06251627
NNNN
00:01 00:01 g # PAB
</P>
</TEXT>
