<HEADLINE> 100 Muslim Rebels Killed in Southern Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 25 (Xinhua) -- Over 100 rebels of the Moro Islamic
Liberation Front (MILF) have been killed during their ongoing
armed conflicts with government troops in Mindanao, the southern
Philippines, the military said today.
</P>
<P>
In a briefing paper, Armed Forces' Chief of Staff Gen. Arnulfo
Acedera said that the military intelligence force reported the
MILF forces suffered 100 casualties during the clashes which
started June 17.
</P>
<P>
But Acedera said that, so far, only 30 bodies of MILF fighters
had been retrieved by the military. MILF fighters usually drag
along their comrades slain during gun battles.
</P>
<P>
Five government soldiers were also killed in the fierce battles
which are now continuing in Pikit town in North Cotabato province
and Sultan Sa Barongis town in Maguindanao province, according to
the military chief.
</P>
<P>
As of 4:00 p.m. Tuesday, there was an on-going firefight
between the MILF and government forces in Pikit but there was no
report yet of any casualty.
</P>
<P>
The clashes, the fiercest so far this year, were triggered off
by a massive hostage-taking incident by the MILF guerrillas last
week.
</P>
<P>
On June 16, 43 employees of the National Oil Company were
seized hostage by the MILF elements in Maguindanao, but they were
successfully rescued by the military the following day.
</P>
<P>
Following the kidnapping incident, the military used land, air
and sea forces to strike the MILF rebels who have been long
suspected as involved in many kidnap-for-ransom activities in
Mindanao.
</P>
<P>
At least four brigades are now conducting operations against
the MILF in central Mindanao, said Acedera, adding that about
2,000 of the estimated 9,000 MILF members are involved in current
conflicts.
</P>
<P>
Also today, Defense Secretary Renato de Villa stressed that the
military will continue its current offensive against the MILF
kidnappers.
</P>
<P>
But the MILF leadership, which has bluntly dismissed the
government's charge that MILF rebels were kidnappers, earlier
warned that the MILF would pull out of the initial peace talks
with the government if the current military offensive continued.
</P>
<P>
The fighting has forced at least 30,000 residents to abandon
their homes in the conflict areas.
</P>
<P>
The MILF is a breakaway faction of the former larger Muslim
rebel group -- the Moro National Liberation Front (MNLF), which
has already signed a peace deal with the government to end its
nearly 30 years of separatist movement.
</P>
<P>
The MILF, which refused to be included in the peace deal, began
its own peace talks with the government in January this year,
which have been on-and-off due to sporadic clashes between the two
sides.
</P>
<P>
The MILF and another smaller rebel group, Abu Sayyaf, are the
remaining two Muslim forces fighting the government. The MILF is
currently the largest anti-government force in the country, with
an estimated 10,000 armed members.  
</P>
</TEXT>
