<HEADLINE> Philippines Posts Record-High Payment Surplus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 25 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines registered a
record-high payment surplus of 570 million U.S. dollars during the
first quarter this year, the Philippine News Agency reported
today.
</P>
<P>
Central bank governor Gabriel Singson was quoted as saying that
the record performance was a result of huge capital inflows which
more than offset the deficit in the country's current account.
</P>
<P>
The current account resulted in an actual deficit of 1.1
billion dollars, or 22 percent higher than the year-ago level of
923 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
But he explained that the transfer account eventually recorded
a surplus of 200 million dollars, or a growth of 16.3 percent from
the year-ago level.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he said the surplus for the service account,
including remittances from overseas Filipino workers and
tourism-related services, netted 1.6 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Singson said that the country's gross official foreign reserves
stood at 11.9 billion dollars as of March 1997, which is
equivalent to 3.1 months of imports of goods and services.
</P>
</TEXT>
