<HEADLINE> Euro Row Unleashed within German Ruling Coalition </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, June 25 (Xinhua) -- A row over Europe's planned single
currency erupted today in Germany, with leaders in Chancellor
Helmut Kohl's ruling coalition trading public accusations.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister of the southern German state of Bavaria,
Edmund Stoiber, sparked the row when he pledged "fierce
resistance" to any attempt by Kohl to soften the membership
criteria for the single currency to allow it to be launched on
time on January 1, 1999.
</P>
<P>
Stoiber said in the German daily Frankfurter Allgemeine Zeitung
that his Christian Social Union, the Bavarian sister party of Kohl's
Christian Democratic Union, would not tolerate any softening of the
strict budgetary benchmark required for qualification for the new
currency, the Euro.
</P>
<P>
He also criticized Kohl for not being assertive enough on the
strict adherence to the Euro criteria.
</P>
<P>
Reacting to Stoiber's remarks, Wolfgang Gerhardt, leader of
Free Democratic Party, the junior partner in Kohl's three-party
ruling coalition, accused Stoiber of using the objection to the
punctual start of the Euro to win popularity, apparently with an
eye on next year's state elections in Bavaria. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
