<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Orders for Durable Goods Decline in May </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 25 (Xinhua) -- Orders for durable goods in the
U.S. declined by 0.6 percent in May, the second drop of this year,
the U.S. Commerce Department reported today.
</P>
<P>
The report said that orders for durable goods, items expected
to last for three or more years, dropped to a seasonally adjusted
176.1 billion dollars last month.
</P>
<P>
That followed a 1.8 percent increase in April and a 2.8 percent
drop in March.
</P>
<P>
May's drop in new orders was widespread except for a strong
10.4 increase in electronic equipment led by demand for electronic
components and communications equipment.
</P>
<P>
Transportation orders fell 3.3 percent with declines in motor
vehicles and aircraft. Orders for primary metals such as steel
decreased 2.4 percent and for industrial machinery 1 percent.
Orders for military goods plunged 12.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
Shipments of durable goods, a measure of current production,
declined by 1.2 percent in May to a seasonally adjusted 176.3
billion dollars after a gain of 1.3 percent in April and 0.8
percent in March.
</P>
<P>
In line with the easing pressure, the backlog of unfilled
orders for durable goods was unchanged at a seasonally adjusted
496.5 billion dollars in May, after falling in both April and
March.
</P>
<P>
The report is further evidence that U.S. economic growth slowed
sharply in the second quarter after soaring at a 5.8 percent
annual rate in the first quarter, the fastest in nearly a decade.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
