<HEADLINE> UK PM Unveils Plan for Disarming N. Irish Guerrillas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 25 (Xinhua) -- British Prime Minister Tony Blair
today unveiled an Anglo-Irish proposal for disarming guerrillas in
Northern Ireland in hopes of putting new life into the stalled
peace process in the divided province.
</P>
<P>
"I appeal to all the parties to look at the proposals in a
constructive spirit. I really do not believe there is another way
forward," the prime minister said.
</P>
<P>
In his speech to parliament, Blair detailed his plan to achieve
a permanent peace in Northern Ireland, which includes setting up
an independent commission to oversee disarmament in parallel with
talks on a lasting political settlement, which Blair hoped to
start in earnest by early September at the latest and conclude by
next May.
</P>
<P>
The key point was that the anti-British Irish Republican Army
(IRA) and its rival Protestant guerrillas would give up their arms
in stages while talks proceeded.
</P>
<P>
He also warned Sinn Fein, the political wing of the IRA, to
rethink its policies and take positive steps to join the peace
process.
</P>
<P>
"The time is limited, the settlement train is leaving, with or
without Sinn Fein. If they want to join, it is absolutely clear
what they have to do. I have dealt straight with them. I expect
straight dealing in return. We and the other parties will not be
waiting around for them," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
Sinn Fein has been excluded from the multi-party peace talks on
the Northern Ireland future because IRA resisted to call a
ceasefire. Sinn Fein quit a 17-month truce in February 1996 and
resumed military campaign to end the British rule in the Northern
Ireland.
</P>
<P>
Blair said an unequivocal restoration of the ceasefire the IRA
broke early last year was needed to win a seat at the peace
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
The British government broke with official contacts with Sinn
Fein last week after two police officers were gunned down while on
their routine patrol by IRA guerrillas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
