<HEADLINE> Chirac Says France Backs Intervention in Congo Republic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, June 25 (Xinhua) -- French President Jacques Chirac
today pledged support to the sending of an African intervention
force in the Congo Republic, but said French troops will only
provide technical support.
</P>
<P>
He made the announcement after a meeting with Senegalese
President Abdou Diouf and President Henri Konan Bedie of Cote
d'Ivoire, who suggested sending the force.
</P>
<P>
"France is surely favorable to all cooperation with the
African states, with the African chief of states for what concerns
the organization of the security. It (France) is ready to
cooperate as they hope and as they ask," said Chirac.
</P>
<P>
Fighting has been going on between forces supporting Congolese
President Pascal Lissouba and "Cobras" militiamen of former
President Denis Sassou-N'Guesso since June 5, in which 1,000 to
3,000 people, most of them civilians, were estimated to have been
killed.
</P>
<P>
"We have done what was necessary to safeguard the life of the
victims of these events and we hope that, in all the situation of
crisis, an inter-African force, under the control of the OAU
(Organization of African Unity) and the countries concerned, could
take the necessary initiatives," said Chirac.
</P>
<P>
But he added: "France, without any doubt, will associate not
by joining the force itself, but with technical aid and support to
this force." 
</P>
</TEXT>
