<HEADLINE> Mandela Reiterates Importance of Having Olympics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 25 (Xinhua) -- South Africa is deeply
committed to having the 2004 Olympic Games held in Cape Town
since sports are a great force for unity and reconciliation,
President Nelson Mandela said today.
</P>
<P>
"If we are nominated to stage the Olympic Games of 2004, we
can assure you that it will be an African Olympics, and an event
of which the entire world will be very proud," Mandela said while
accepting the Pierre de Coubertin Fair Play Award in Pretoria.
</P>
<P>
The award, named after the founder of the Modern OLympic
Movement, was conferred by International Olympic Committee (IOC)
member Louis Guirandou N'diaye, who is Acting President of the
International Committee for Fair Play.
</P>
<P>
Mandela said that Africa had been in the forefront of the
fight against apartheid, adding that many of its potential
medalists withdrew from the 1976 Olympics in protest against
racial oppression in South Africa.
</P>
<P>
"We believe that the road towards 2004 will accelerate the
healing and reconstruction process, not only in South Africa but
on the entire (African) continent," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
