<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German Parliament Approves Law on Organ Donation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, June 25 (Xinhua) -- German parliament today voted 422 to
213 to legalize the current practice in Germany that family
members can decide whether to donate organs of a deceased person
or not for transplanting.
</P>
<P>
The parliament rejected the bill proposing that the removal of
organs must get the donor's signed agreement before his or her
death.
</P>
<P>
This issue had been the focus in the debate which had divided
all factions in the parliament. Party leaders told deputies to
vote according to their conscience instead of any party line.
</P>
<P>
Among those voting for the passed law were Health Minister
Horst Seehofer, and leader of the main opposition Social Democrats
(SPD), Rudolf Scharping, and those voting for the stricter bill
that lost included Justice Minister Edzard Schmidt-Jortzig and
most of opposition Greens Party deputies.
</P>
<P>
Supporters of the passed law noted that of the 3,228 organ
transplants in German hospitals in 1996, only 34 cases used organs
which people had pledged before their death.
</P>
<P>
Under the new law, people can also expressly forbid any organs
to be removed from their bodies after their death.
</P>
<P>
The new legislation also allows doctors to remove organs from
people who, at a minimum, have been declared to be brain-dead by
two doctors, neither of whom is involved in organ transplants.
Some deputies had proposed to allow removal of organs from
brain-dead people but had wanted to bar such people from being
legally declared dead.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
