<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-25 16:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> All Set for Direct Talks on Cyprus Issue: U.N. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, June 25 (Xinhua) -- A U.N. official said everything is
ready for the holding of Cypriot bi-communal direct talks near New
York next month, but expecting no "magic thing" out of them soon.
</P>
<P>
Telling reporters after meeting with Cypriot President Glafcos
Clerides, U.N. resident representative to Cyprus Gustave Feissel
confirmed that leaders of the Greek and Turkish communities in
Cyprus will be attending the talks.
</P>
<P>
He said that U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan has received a
verbal confirmation from Greek and Turkish Cypriot sides of their
attendance of the talks scheduled between July 9 to 13.
</P>
<P>
Feissel said that "when I visited both leaders to give the
letter from the Secretary-General, I was told by both orally they
were going to be there. So, we are not waiting for any
reply. Everything is ready. There is nothing outstanding."
</P>
<P>
The forthcoming U.N.-sponsored direct talks between Clerides
and Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Dankash are aimed at hammering out
a comprehensive solution to the protracted Cyprus problem.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, Feissel provided Clerides with further
"logistical information" on the talks.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. envoy refrained from speculating about the outcome of
the talks, saying that "one should not expect some magic thing
coming out of this first meeting."
</P>
<P>
Feissel said that the international community expects both
sides to proceed to the direct negotiations with a very serious
intent and to make a real concrete contribution toward a
comprehensive settlement.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. official pointed out that although representatives of
the parties involved will be closely monitoring the talks from
nearby, the meeting will be "strictly between the two sides and
the U.N.."
</P>
<P>
The Cyprus issue has remained unresolved since 1974 when the
island was divided into the Greek Cypriot south and the Turkish
Cypriot north after the Turkish troops occupied its northern
third in the wake of a pro-Athens coup. 
</P>
</TEXT>
