<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU-Japan Summit Ends, Trade Surplus Dialogue Underway </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
THE HAGUE, June 25 (Xinhua) -- Japan agreed to step up its
dialogue with the European Union on curbing the trade imbalance
and further opening some of its market as the annual EU-Japan
summit ended here today.
</P>
<P>
The half-day meeting, which brought together Japanese Prime
Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto, European Commission President Jacques
Santer and Dutch Prime Minister and current EU rotating president
Wim Kok, is the sixth since the two sides met for their first
Summit of this kind in 1991, when they signed the EU-Japan Joint
Declaration in this Dutch capital.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a joint press conference after the meeting, Kok
said the two sides had agreed to continue and step up the dialogue
on Japan's deregulation program, designed to curb its trade
surplus with Europe and encourage European investment in Japan.
</P>
<P>
Japan also agreed to recognize the quality testing of European
medical equipment from September 1 this year, thus exempting EU's
medical devices from inspection in Japan.
</P>
<P>
"The present relationship between the Union and Japan can be
characterized by the words of dialogue, cooperation and
partnership," he said, "There is a strong determination from both
sides for further deepening this relationship," Kok said.
</P>
<P>
Kok described the summit as valuable and encouraging, saying it
has laid the basis for further cooperation between EU and Japan.
</P>
<P>
Also describing the meeting as "meaningful", the Japanese Prime
Minister said that the two sides were now resolving pending issues
"one by one through cool-headed discussions".
</P>
<P>
Expressing understanding for EU's concerns for the sharp
increase of Japan's trade surplus with EU during the first five
months this year, Hashimoto said that he believed it would be
temporary and that he believed it would not increase in middle and
long terms.
</P>
<P>
While agreeing to accelerate talks in economic issue, both
sides have stressed at the meeting that much more attention should
be put on their political cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Hashimoto said that Japan-EU relationship should be further
strengthened to ensure the economic weight of the two leads to
also responsibility being taken for political talks.
</P>
<P>
His view was shared by Santer who said that EU and Japan were
no longer just economic partners. "We are building a powerful
political alliance to advance our common interests at the world
stage both in Europe as well as in Asia," he said.
</P>
<P>
Santer also told reporters that the EU and Japan had affirmed
their joint commitment to give momentum to the talks for China's
bid  for the World Trade Organization (WTO).
</P>
<P>
A joint statement issued after the meeting also said that the
two sides had agreed to cooperate more closely in issues such as
welfare, environment, fighting against organized crime and drugs.
</P>
<P>
At the meeting, Kok briefed his guest last week's EU Amsterdam
summit at which a new EU treaty had been agreed, and the process
of establishing the Economic and Monetary Union due to be launched
on January 1, 1999.
</P>
<P>
The two sides also discussed a range of international issues
including the latest situations in Cambodia, Bosnia, and the
Middle East peace process. 
</P>
