<HEADLINE> Second Session of Somali Salvation Council Opens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, June 25 (Xinhua) -- The second ordinary session
of the National Salvation Council (NSC) of Somalia opened
here today, seeking ways of bringing final peace to the war-torn
country.
</P>
<P>
Opening the second session, NSC current chairman Ali Mahdi
Mohamed said Somalia is definitely in a better condition now than
six months ago.
</P>
<P>
He added that in accordance with the Sodere agreement reached
at the first session, the Executive Committee of the NSC has
appointed two co-chairmen to enter dialogue with Hussein Mohamed
Aideed for peace in Mogadishu and to convince him to join the
peace process spearheaded by the National Salvation Council.
</P>
<P>
"As a result of this mandated mission, peace agreements have
been concluded in Sanaa, Yemen and Cairo, Egypt," he said, adding
that "since those agreements, peace has returned to Mogadishu and
the relation between the National Salvation Council and Hussein
Aideed faction has been improving steadily."
</P>
<P>
Mahdi told participants that Somalia as a whole is in relative
peace and stability today. However, he said that the fighting in
middle and lower Jubba regions is a sad occurrence that must be
stopped immediatedly and prevented.
</P>
<P>
He condemned the illegal occupation by Hussein Aideed against
the will of the native inhabitants and called for the withdrawal
of forces unconditionally from these regions.
</P>
<P>
Mahdi said, "the Somali people yearned for peace, tranquility,
stability and restoration of their dignity as a nation beyond
petty clan differences, political bricking and insignificant
pickings."
</P>
<P>
He urged the fellow council members to put aside all
personal differences and act collectively for the common goal of
securing the welfare of the Somali people by rebuilding their
country.
</P>
<P>
On the same occasion, Ethiopian Vice-minister of Foreign
Affairs Tekeda Alemu assured his country's support to the Somali
peace process and said that Ethiopia will continue to do whatever
is necessary and within the limits of its capacity for the
realization of peace and national reconciliation in Somalia.
</P>
<P>
The 7-day second session will move to Sodere, 130 kms away
from Addis Ababa from tomorrow. 
</P>
</TEXT>
