<HEADLINE> S. African Individuals to be Allowed to Invest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 25 (Xinhua) -- South African individuals
will be allowed to invest up to 200,000 Rand (4,444 U.S. Dollars)
abroad from July 1, the South African Ministry of Finance
announced in Pretoria today.
</P>
<P>
The amount may be dealt with in any manner that the investor
deems fit, the ministry said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
The move forms part of the South African government's program
to relax foreign exchange controls gradually, the South African
Press Association said.
</P>
<P>
According to the statement, direct investment abroad has risen
substantially, and many international corporations have
re-entered the country.
</P>
<P>
Besides, applications to invest in fixed property in Southern
African Development Community countries, such as holiday homes
and farms, will also be considered from the beginning of next
month.
</P>
<P>
Institutional investors, such as corporations, insurance
companies, pension funds and unit trust have so far invested 27.7
billion Rand (6.16 billion U.S. Dollars) abroad, the ministry
said.
</P>
<P>
It said it believed the new measures will boost domestic and
international confidence in the South African economy and lay the
foundation for the further liberalization of foreign exchange
controls. 
</P>
</TEXT>
