<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Annan Recommends Two-phase U.N. Withdrawal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS June 25 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General Kofi
Annan today proposed a two-phase exit strategy for the withdrawal
of the United Nations Transitional Administration for Eastern
Slavonia (UNTAES).
</P>
<P>
In his report to the Security Council, Annan said the pace of
the handover to Croatian control would be commensurable with
Croatia's performance in reassuring the Serb population and
peacefully reintegrating the region.
</P>
<P>
In the proposed first phase of withdrawal, the number of the
U.N. troops would be halved by mid-August from 5,000 to 2,530,
including 720 military support personnel.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, Transitional Administrator would also devolve
to Croatia executive responsibility for the major part of civil
administration of the region while maintaining his authority and
ability to intervene and overrule decisions should the situation
deteriorate and the achievements of UNTAES be threatened.
</P>
<P>
In the second phase, and subject to satisfactory Croatian
performance, remaining executive functions would be devolved, with
Croatia resuming responsibility for the continued demilitarization
of the region and the gradual integration of the Transitional
Police Force into the Croatian authorities.
</P>
<P>
"Further reductions are planned for the period after September
in order to reach a level of 720 by October in the light of
developments of the country," Annan said.
</P>
<P>
Annan stressed the essential prerequisite was the the full
cooperation of the Croatian government which bore the
responsibility of convincing the local population that
reintegration of the people of the region was sustainable and that
the process of reconciliation and return was irreversible.
</P>
<P>
Under the 1995 Dayton peace accords, UNTAES was established to
oversee the reintegration of the heavily Serb-inhabited region of
Eastern Slavonia into Croatia.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
