<DOCNO> XIE19970626.0031 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK Bank Governor Warns on Single Currency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 25 (Xinhua) -- Eddie George, the governor of the
Bank of England, last night gave his strongest warning yet that
Europe's unemployment problem may make it dangerous to go ahead
with the single currency.
</P>
<P>
The move would be fraught with risk if some member countries
had not improved the flexibility of their job markets, the
governor told his audience at the City University Business School.
</P>
<P>
"I am frankly nervous at the prospect of introducing the euro
at a time of very high and very different rates of unemployment
across Europe," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Governor warned that labor market reform must be an urgent
priority for European governments, saying "we have to find answers
to the urgent problem of European unemployment."
</P>
<P>
His warning came as the pound hit a five-year high. Observers
in the City said investors were continuing to transfer funds out
of the major European currencies and into "safe" currencies such
as sterling and the dollar.
</P>
<P>
"We are not all starting from the same station", the Governor
said, before pointing out that "the possibility of such cyclical
divergences will not simply disappear on January 1, 1999, and they
would seriously complicate the operation of monetary policy."
</P>
<P>
Eddie George support the government's emphasis at the recent
Amsterdam summit on the use of supply-side reforms to boost
employment. But he added that there was not yet consensus in
Europe on specific measures.
</P>
<P>
"If we are to be able to hold on to macroeconomic stability -
as we must - then we have to find answers to the urgent problem of
European unemployment," the Governor said.
</P>
<P>
But stable macroeconomic policies were not enough, as
illustrated by the fact that output had stagnated and unemployment
risen inexorably, he added.
</P>
<P>
The Governor conceded that unemployment in Europe - which
averages more than one in 10 of the workforce - was probably
aggravated by the "heroic attempts being made to meet the fiscal
criteria according to the Maastricht criteria in a context of
cyclical weakness". 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
