<DOCNO> XIE19970626.0032 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Existing Home Sales Up Sharply in May </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 25 (Xinhua) -- Sales of previously owned homes
in the U.S. jumped by 4.4 percent in May to the highest level this
year, the U.S. National Association of Realtors reported today.
</P>
<P>
The report said that single-family homes sold at a seasonally
adjusted annual rate of 4.24 million in May, up from 4.06 million
in April. That was just 0.9 percent under the record 4.28 million
sales rate of May 1996.
</P>
<P>
Regionally, sales rose 8.2 percent in the South to a rate of
1.46 million and 5.9 percent in the Midwest to 1.07 million. Sales
in the West were unchanged at a rate of 930,000. They edged 1.5
percent lower in the Northeast to 660,000.
</P>
<P>
"We expect fairly stable sales for the balance of the year,"
said the association's president, Russell Booth. That would bring
sales in at about the 18-year high of 4.09 million reached last
year.
</P>
<P>
The increasing sales of existing homes were supported by the
highest level of consumer confidence in nearly 30 years and the
lowest rate of unemployment in 24 years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
