<DOCNO> XIE19970626.0034 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Bank WDR Reports: Rethinking The State </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 25 (Xinhua) --The World Bank today issued a
report asserting an "effective state" is the cornerstone of
successful economies, and without it, economic and social
development is impossible.
</P>
<P>
According to the 265-page World Development Report 1997: the
State in a Changing World, those countries which have concluded
that the role of the state should be less prominent, ought to
consider how the dazzling growth of East Asia, and even the
industrial revolution, were made possible by an "effective
state"--- one which harnesses the energy of private business and
individuals, and acts as their partner and catalyst, instead of
restricting their partnership.
</P>
<P>
The report underlined several key tasks for every government's
mission: establishing a foundation of law, maintaining an
effective macroeconomic policy environment, including capable
financial institutions, investing in basic social services and
infrastructure, providing a comprehensive safety net for
vulnerable members of society and protecting the environment.
</P>
<P>
A survey of entrepreneurs in 69 countries was used to gauge
government credibility and its impact on business. In general, it
shows a strong correlation between a country's credibility rating
and its record of growth and private investment.
</P>
<P>
Specifically, the survey reveals that many countries lack the
basic institutional foundations for markets to grow. High levels
of crime and personal violence and an unpredictable judiciary
combine to produce what the report defines as the "lawlessness
syndrome."
</P>
<P>
Cutting back on discretionary authority on the part of
government is essential, the WDR report stressed. Policies
that lower controls on foreign trade, remove entry barriers for
private industry, and privatize state firms in a way that ensures
competition will help fight corruption. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
