<HEADLINE> UNITA Worried over Angola's Peace Process </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, June 25 (Xinhua) -- An official from the National
Union for the Total Independence of Angola (UNITA) today
expressed worries over the peace process in the country.
</P>
<P>
Isaias Samakuva, head of UNITA's delegation at the Joint
Commission of Angolan Peace Process, told the press in Bailundo,
central Angola, that the current situation in Angola was similar
to the one in 1992 when a civil war re-erupted in the southern
African country.
</P>
<P>
UNITA does not want to see Angola once again plunged into a
civil war, which would bring great losses to the people, Samakuva
said.
</P>
<P>
The UNITA official attributed the recent clashes between UNITA
army and government forces in the country's northeastern
diamond-mining area to government attacks, saying UNITA did not
launch an offensive.
</P>
<P>
The peace process requires a stable environment, said
Samakuva, who then called on all sides concerned to stop hostile
military operations and come back to the Lusaka Peace Agreement.
</P>
<P>
The Angolan peace process is presently caught in a stalemate
due to both disputes on the establishment of local
administrations and fights between government forces and UNITA
army in the diamond-mining areas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
