<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. House Approves Defense Budget </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 25 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. House of
Representatives today approved a 268.2 billion U.S. dollars
defense budget for the fiscal year of 1998.
</P>
<P>
The defense bill, passed by the House on a bipartisan vote of
304-210, provides 285 million U.S. dollars to destroy Russia's
Cold War-era nuclear weapons.
</P>
<P>
The representatives also voted for purchasing another nine B-2
bombers. Cohen was opposed to the purchase, arguing it is too
expensive and unnecessary.
</P>
<P>
The bill authorized 2.1 billion U.S. dollars as requested by
the White House for continued development of the Air Force's F-22
fighter. It also would spend 1.3 billion U.S. dollars for up to 12
F/A-18 E and F planes.
</P>
<P>
The Senate is expected to vote on a defense bill next month.
</P>
<P>
Both the House and Senate defense bills would spend 6.6 billion
U.S. dollars more than President Bill Clinton requested and are
three billion larger than the 1997 budget.
</P>
<P>
The B-2 production start-up may not survive the legislative
process as the Senate version expressly bars purchase of
additional B-2 aircraft.
</P>
<P>
Cohen said the Pentagon was unanimous in its view that "the
cost of further B-2 production cannot be justified."
</P>
<P>
But supporters argued the funds would help maintain productive
capacity of the defense industry and provide necessary fighting
capability. 
</P>
</TEXT>
