<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Business Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 25 (Xinhua) -- The following are business briefs
from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Samsung Electronics Co., the South Korean
industrial giant, is expected to open a research development
center in Israel within a year, reported The Jerusalem Post today.
</P>
<P>
Jong Goo Li, the company's Israel-based representative, made
the announcement during a ceremony to celebrate the opening of
the company's office in Herzliya Pituah, north of Tel Aviv,
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The company does not yet know the size of the investment it
will make in the center, which will be located either near
Technion in Haifa or in Herzliya Pituah, said Jong.
</P>
<P>
Researchers will focus on developing telecommunications
technologies, semiconductor and software in the center, he said.
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- Royal Wings, a subsidiary of Jordan's national
airline Royal Jordan (RJ), signed an agreement here Tuesday with
Jordanian and Israeli hotels and tourist offices to promote
tourism between Amman and the Israeli northern city Haifa, Jordan
Times reported today.
</P>
<P>
The agreement stipulates that Royal Wings organizes flights
between the two cities, transporting tourists to either city for
a four-day stay.
</P>
<P>
The tourists are arranged to stay in five-star hotels and visit
the tourist sites in the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Signatories of the agreement include Jordan's Forte Grand Hotel
and Royal Tours, and Dan Karmel Hotel, Dan Panorama Hotel,
Nazarine Tours in Haifa, the Haifa Tourists Promotion Office as
well as its tourism program development department.
</P>
<P>
The airline, which owns two planes with 50 seats each, has been
operating two daily flights between the Jordanian cities of Amman
and Aqaba and a weekly flight from Amman to the Egyptian city of
Sharm el-Sheikh.
</P>
<P>
TUNIS -- Tunisia and the Islamic Development Bank signed an
agreement here today on cooperation in activating technical
assistance between member states of the Organization of the
Islamic Conference (OIC).
</P>
<P>
The agreement has appointed the Tunisian Agency for Technical
Assistance as the liaison officer in charge of coordination.
</P>
<P>
The agreement stipulates Tunisia's preparedness to develop the
financial and technical capabilities of the OIC developing member
states with a view to enabling them to benefit from the available
financial opportunities, and the exchange of expertise
particularly in the field of consultative services.
</P>
<P>
The agreement also defines the mechanisms of the tripartite
cooperation between Tunisia, the Islamic Development Bank and the
developing Islamic countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
