<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Americans Concerned about Children's Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 25 (Xinhua) -- Americans express deep concern
over the moral and ethical development of the nation's children
and don't see parents as adequate role models.
</P>
<P>
A survey released Wednesday indicates 37 percent of the 2,000
people surveyed believe today's children will make the country a
better place once they're grown, The United Press International
reported from Chicago.
</P>
<P>
The Kids These Days survey was conducted by Public Agenda for
Ronald McDonald House Charities and the Advertising Council.
</P>
<P>
Those surveyed were critical of both teenagers and young
children. Teens were described as rude, irresponsible and wild.
Younger children were described as lacking discipline and spoiled.
</P>
<P>
Only 12 percent said it is common for children to treat people
with respect.
</P>
<P>
Public Agenda Executive Director Deborah Wadsworth says,
"Americans are frightened for and in some cases frightened of our
children and fault parents for the problems they see."
</P>
<P>
Parents were criticized for being too willing to break up their
marriages instead of trying to stay together for the children.
</P>
<P>
The survey also queried children 12 to 17 years old. Nearly
half said they feel children their age need more guidance and
attention from adults. Only a third said they think their
generation will make the world a better place. 
</P>
</TEXT>
