<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-25 19:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkish PM-Designate Optimistic About New </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, June 25 (Xinhua) -- Turkish Prime Minister designate
Mesut Yilmaz today expressed optimism about the new government
that he is trying to form.
</P>
<P>
Following a meeting with President Suleyman Demirel, Yilmaz
told reporters that his contacts with several parties made him
believe that the new government would win a vote of confidence.
</P>
<P>
Yilmaz, chairman of the second largest Motherland Party
(ANAP), made the remark after the Welfare Party (RP) and the True
Path Party (DYP) announced that they had enough votes to defeat
the proposed government in the parliament.
</P>
<P>
Outgoing Prime Minister Necmettin Erbakan told a press
conference that the only thing that Yilmaz should do was to
return the mandate to the president, saying a RP-DYP alliance
with the Grand Unity Party (BBP) support would form a
parliamentary majority.
</P>
<P>
Yilmaz, however, categorically rejected the RP-DYP
announcement, saying that he would form the new government at the
end of his talks with other party leaders.
</P>
<P>
"I believe that the developments in the coming days will
expand the margin. The outcome of the vote will not be very
close," the ANAP leader added.
</P>
<P>
Describing it as unfair that the RP and DYP leaders' allegation
that he was trying to recruit deputies from these parties, Yilmaz
said that deputies had right to make their own decisions.
</P>
<P>
Yilmaz has reportedly briefed Demirel on the developments of
his work to set up a new government to replace the outgoing RP-DYP
administration.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that he would go ahead with his program to form
a new government without making any direction changes, adding he
would not hold new talks with DYP leader Tansu Ciller unless she
changed her stance.
</P>
<P>
Turkey's three major opposition parties, which have more than
100 seats in the parliament, have expressed their support for the
new government to be formed by Yilmaz.
</P>
<P>
Ciller, however, refused to discuss government issue with
Yilmaz on Tuesday during their 20-minute meeting, urging Yilmaz
to return the mandate to the president.
</P>
<P>
If the new government fails to win a vote of confidence in the
parliament, the mandate to form a government has to go to Ciller's
DYP, which is the third largest party in the legislature.
</P>
<P>
For the time being, Yilmaz has enjoyed 265 votes in the
parliament, not enough to survive a possible vote of confidence in
the 550-seat parliament with a vacancy of two.
</P>
<P>
Erbakan, under pressure and criticism from the military and the
junior coalition partner DYP over his government's failure to curb
the rapidly expanding Islamic fundamentalism in the secular
country, resigned on June 18. 
</P>
</TEXT>
