<DOCNO> XIE19970626.0046 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> GCC Nearly Finishes Commodities Classification </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, June 25 (Xinhua) -- The Gulf Cooperation Council
(GCC) states nearly finished the process of commodities
classification today in Riyadh, capital of Saudi Arabia, to pave
way for forging unified customs tariffs on foreign imports.
</P>
<P>
Reports reaching here from Riyadh said that the GCC customs
committee finalized the classification of 34 commodities out of 70.
</P>
<P>
The Kuwait News Agency (Kuna) quoted the reports as saying
the committee finalized, during its 11th meeting last Monday, the
classification of 312 commodities, after agreement by some states
who had objected earlier, bringing the agreed items to 94.5
percent of about 1,400 items on the generally accepted
international classification list.
</P>
<P>
The GCC, a regional political and economic organization founded
in 1981, groups Saudi Arabia, Kuwait, the United Arab Emirates,
Oman, Qatar and Bahrain.
</P>
<P>
Customs tariffs in the GCC states at present vary from 4
percent to 25 percent.
</P>
<P>
A wide gap existed among the member states toward the
unification due to differences in each country's economic
priorities. The disagreement has blocked a tariffs agreement
almost since the alliance was formed.
</P>
<P>
The classification of goods falls into three categories,
including goods exempted from tariffs, basic goods with a tariff
of 4 to 8 percent or 8 to 12 percent, and other goods.
</P>
<P>
Differences on classifying the remaining 36 center on the
rate of customs to be imposed, KUNA said.
</P>
<P>
The GCC Financial and Economic Cooperation Committee decided
in its 45th meeting held in Doha, Qatar, last May that the
customs committee should classify all the unclassified
commodities, and the list of the newly-classified commodities
would be referred to the committee during its next meeting in
October.
</P>
<P>
The final authority deciding the issue would be the GCC heads
of state who will hold their annual summit in Kuwait in December.
</P>
<P>
Sources close to the committee described the progress in
efforts to achieve the customs unification by the GCC states as
"a great success toward achieving a strong economic bloc in the
face of other international alliances." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970626.0047 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-26 </DATE_TIME>
