<HEADLINE> Voters' Registration Begins in Liberia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, June 25 (Xinhua) -- Voters' registration for the July
19 presidential and parliamentary elections began today in Liberia,
after a day's delay by torrential rain and transportation problems.
</P>
<P>
In Monrovia and its environs, registration began at many
schools and public buildings around 7:00 a.m., with the west
African peace-keeping force providing security for hundreds of
queuing civilians, a report reaching here said.
</P>
<P>
The peacekeeping force and the United Nations observers today
also started airlifting registrars assigned to remote areas, the
report said.
</P>
<P>
About one million Liberians above the age of 18 are eligible
for the poll, which will produce the future president, the
vice-president and 90 legislators.
</P>
<P>
Altogether 13 candidates have announced their intentions to
contest for the presidency.
</P>
<P>
It is widely expected that the election will lead to final peace in
Liberia, after seven years of civil war that has killed over 200,000
people and left many others homeless.
</P>
<P>
Also today, Commander of the peacekeeping force Victor Malu
called on the UN High Commissioner for Refugees to lend a helping
hand to the refugees that have been voluntarily returning to
Liberia through various border posts.
</P>
<P>
The commander estimated that about 140,000 Liberians have returned
home in the last two months. He noted the refugees need help to settle
down in their war-devastated towns and villages. 
</P>
</TEXT>
