<HEADLINE> Kenyan Opposition MPs Reject Budget Debate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 25 (Xinhua) -- Kenyan opposition members of
parliament (MP) today continued to reject participation in the
on-going debate on the 1997/98 budget report.
</P>
<P>
They staged a mass walkout of the National Assembly on Tuesday
when Kenyan parliament started the seven-day debate on the budget
report made by Finance Minister Musalia Mudavadi last Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Opposition MPs said that they would not take part in any
debate until their suit was heard and determined on Friday
otherwise the debate would prejudice the court proceedings.
</P>
<P>
The suit filed by seven Opposition MPs last Monday is aimed at
seeking to stop parliament from debating the budget report and
will be argued next Friday.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the suit, Kenyan President Daniel arap Moi said
on Tuesday that parliament was supreme and cannot therefore be
taken to court.
</P>
<P>
Kenyan Speaker Francis Ole Kaparo also noted that no authority
in the east African country had any power to interfere with the
business of parliament.
</P>
<P>
He termed the move taken by Opposition MPs as "the grossest
insult to the House, an abuse of privileges and a subversion of
the rules and powers of the House."
</P>
<P>
Velarie Onyango, Chief Litigation Counsel, told Kenyan High
Court on Tuesday that the chaos which rocked parliament last
Thursday were caused by Opposition leaders themselves and hence
"they should not take advantage of their own undoings to hold the
state at ransom."
</P>
<P>
She noted that parliament had operated under special powers
and privileges which barred courts of law from any kind of
interferences. 
</P>
</TEXT>
