<HEADLINE> Namibia to Reform Intelligence Service </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 25 (Xinhua) -- Namibian Prime Minister Hage
Geingob today assured the nation that a proposed legislation to
regulate the country's intelligence is not aimed to harass the
public but protect them.
</P>
<P>
There are sufficient safeguards built into the Central
Intelligence Service Bill to avoid misuse of power by the state
agents, Geingob was quoted by local press as saying.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister told a press conference in Windhoek that
there will be no bugging of private telephones or interception of
mail unless permission for such acts is granted by a judge.
</P>
<P>
He said the intelligence bill has become necessary due to internal
threats such as instigation of ethnic strife, labour unrest, tax fraud
and terrorism.
</P>
<P>
There are also external threats to Namibia posed by drug dealers,
arms smugglers and the illegal plundering of resources such as
diamonds and fish, he added. 
</P>
