<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Attorney General Backs Constitutional Amendment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 25 (Xinhua) -- A constitutional amendment to
require that crime victims are notified and permitted to attend
court proceedings is the best way to protect their rights, U.S.
Attorney General Janet Reno said today.
</P>
<P>
"There are too many victims in this country who feel like they
are left out of the system," Reno told the Judiciary Committee of
the House of Representatives.
</P>
<P>
Witnesses who appeared later criticized the proposed amendment,
saying that while the goal was worthy, the approach was
unworkable.
</P>
<P>
Proponents said that the Constitution includes at least 15
specific rights for defendants but none for crime victims, an
omission they contend allows the system to disregard victims and
their pain.
</P>
<P>
Under the amendment, victims would be told of court proceedings
and allowed to attend, permitted to make statements about a
release, plea bargain or sentence and be notified of a prisoner's
escape or release.
</P>
<P>
It also would grant victims the right to restitution and
require that their safety be considered before their assailants'
release.
</P>
<P>
Reno said an amendment ensuring these rights is the "best
means" to correct the "existing imbalance... between defendants'
constitutional rights and the current haphazard patchwork of
victims' rights."
</P>
<P>
Some 29 states have added victims' rights amendments to their
constitutions, but advocates of a federal amendment -- applicable
to state and federal court proceedings -- say state protections
aren't uniform and often are superseded by the defendant rights
outlined in the U.S. Constitution. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970626.0057 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IFC Approves 120 Mln Dlrs for Mozambique Aluminum Plant </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 25 (Xinhua) -- The International Finance
Corporation (IFC) today announced the approval of a 120 million
U.S. dollar investment for the establishment of the Mozal aluminum
smelter project in Maputo, Mozambique.
</P>
<P>
The investment is one of the largest commitments for the IFC's
own account ever approved by the corporation.
</P>
<P>
The project consists of the construction and development of a
245,000-ton-a-year aluminum smelter to be located near the port of
Maputo. The total project cost is estimated to be 1.36 billion
dollars.
</P>
<P>
The IFC financing package includes a quasi-equity investment of
up to 65 million dollars and a loan of up to 55 million dollars.
In addition to the IFC's investment, Gencor Ltd., a South African
metals and mining company and owner of Alusaf Ltd., operator of
one of the world's largest aluminum smelters, is investing some
125 million dollars in equity along with the Industrial
Development Corporation of South Africa which is investing another
125 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
The IFC is a member of the World Bank Group, and the largest
multilateral source of equity and loan financing for private
sector projects in developing countries. Up to date, the IFC has
invested over 11 million dollars for six projects in Mozambique.
</P>
</TEXT>
