<HEADLINE> Rebels Postpone Talks With Philippine Government </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
MANILA, June 26 (Xinhua) -- A Philippine Muslim rebel group
decided today to postpone its peace talks with the government
because of ongoing fierce conflicts between the two sides in
Mindanao, the southern Philippines.
</P>
<P>
Al Hadj Murad, vice chairman of the Moro Islamic Liberation
Front (MILF), told the local television ABS-CBN by telephone that
his group decided to defer the next round of their initial peace
talks with the government in view of the current fighting.
</P>
<P>
The government and the MILF had planned to begin their sixth
round of exploratory peace talks in Maguindanao province in
western Mindanao on June 28 and 29 to discuss a general ceasefire
in the southern Philippines.
</P>
<P>
But Murad, who is in charge of MILF military affairs, did not
say when the delayed peace talks will re-start.
</P>
<P>
MILF Vice Chairman Al Hadj Murad denied their men took some
100 passengers hostage, saying these civilians were just caught in
the cross fire between the soldiers and the MILF fighters.
</P>
<P>
Murad said his men stopped the buses just to prevent them from
going along the highway in North Cotabato province, central
Mindanao, where the MILF is going to lay landmines.
</P>
<P>
He also denied his men shot two passengers.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Gen. Arnulfo Acedera, chief of staff of the Armed
Forces, made it clear that the military will continue its ongoing
offensives against the MILF rebels despite the rebels' threat to
pull out of the peace talks.
</P>
<P>
He said there is "no letup in the military action until all
suspected kidnappers are flashed out of MILF camps."
</P>
<P>
The military chief said the military will continue its ground
and air attacks against the positions of the rebels to save the 40
hostages who remain in the hands of the rebels.
</P>
<P>
A special air force was sent to reinforce the government
troops fighting the MILF in North Cotabato province in central
Mindanao.
</P>
<P>
Today's conflict started at 5:30 a.m. when MILF rebels stopped
three buses along a highway in Kabacan and held hostage some 100
passengers.
</P>
<P>
After a four-hour fierce battle, 60 hostages were rescued by
the military, who were backed by helicopter gunships. The battle
reportedly killed four soldiers, two civilians and one rebel.
</P>
<P>
A group of marine troops were deployed along the highway
linking North Cotabato and Davao province this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Earlier reports said 47 rebels and at least five soldiers were
killed during the fierce clashes between the MILF and the military
in the past 10 days.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
