<DOCNO> XIE19970626.0065 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong's Return Serves as Starting Point for Prosperity </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 26 (Xinhua) -- The upcoming return of Hong Kong
to China will inject a new impetus into the region's economic
development and become a new starting point for its prosperity,
according to an article in the latest issue of the Hong Kong and
Macao Economic Quarterly.
</P>
<P>
Outlining the great impact of this historic event on Hong
Kong's economy, the article said, the transfer of power in Hong
Kong will dispel some people's worries and increase the confidence
of overseas investors.
</P>
<P>
The concept of "one country, two systems" ensures that the key
factors contributing to the success of Hong Kong will stay in
future, and that Hong Kong residents will be able to govern Hong
Kong successfully.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the relations between the inland areas of China and
Hong Kong will be further increased and the "China factor" will
play an increasingly important role in Hong Kong's economic
development.
</P>
<P>
The inland areas have set the long-range economic objective
through the year 2010 and drawn up the Ninth Five-Year Plan
(1996-2000), which will provide more and greater development
opportunities for Hong Kong, the article said.
</P>
<P>
the International Monetary Fund predicted that the global
economy will grow rapidly during the 1997-2002 period. Asia will
be the region that will score the fastest growth in the world and
this is conducive to Hong Kong's economic development.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, Hong Kong will play a greater role as an
international trade center with the improvement of the global
trade environment, it said.
</P>
<P>
In the near future, the growth of personal consumption and
investment in fixed assets will top the expected targets as a
result of the good impact of Hong Kong's return to China.
</P>
<P>
The growth rate of Hong Kong's economy is expected to reach 5.8
percent this year, despite a slow export growth in the first half
of the year, the article said.
</P>
<P>
During the 1998-2002 period, the annual growth rate of Hong
Kong's gross domestic product is expected to increase from an
average of 5.4 percent in the previous five years to six percent,
it said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
