<HEADLINE> Singapore Takes Tougher Measures Against Hard-Core </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Singapore launched this year's
National Anti-Drug Abuse Campaign today with the government
announcing its decision to amend the Misuse of Drugs Act by the
end of the year to take tougher measures against hard-core drug
addicts.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the launching ceremony tonight, Wong Kan Seng,
Minister for Home Affairs, said drug abuse is a national problem
and the problem is "highly volatile and the situation can
deteriorate very quickly".
</P>
<P>
"We will take tougher measures against hard-core drug addicts
to break the vicious cycle of drug addiction and crime," the
Minister declared, adding that the Misuse of Drugs Act will be
amended before the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
Under the proposed amendments, hard-core opiate addicts will be
prosecuted in court and if convicted, they will be given a
mandatory five to seven years jail term with three to six strokes
of the cane.
</P>
<P>
Any addict who has been through the five to seven years jail
term with caning and re-arrested for another opiate drug offense
will be liable for a longer seven to 13 years jail term plus six
to 12 strokes of the cane, Wong said.
</P>
<P>
Although the new regime is targeted at opiate addicts, other
drug abusers are warned that the Government will not hesitate to
impose similar stern measures against them if the situation
warrants it, he added.
</P>
<P>
The Minister also said that though the drug situation in
Singapore is under control and the number of drug addicts arrested
since 1994 has declined, Ecstasy abuse has gone up to date and
more than 700 persons have been prosecuted for Ecstasy abuse since
the problem surfaced in late 1995.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
