<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Before Handover (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 26 (Xinhua) -- It was dawn and most parts of
the city were still asleep, but thousands of news stands already
started a new day of business in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Lee, an old man in his late 50s, was busy placing more than 20
kinds of just-arrived local newspapers onto his small stand near
the Southorn Playground in the downtown district of Wan Chai.
</P>
<P>
"With the handover coming nearer day by day, public concerns
about this big event are growing, and newspapers sell very well
these days," he said with a beaming face.
</P>
<P>
The streets became alive with vehicles and pedestrians after
the clock struck eight. Among the commuters scurrying past, many
are public servants who have been working for years in the tall
and magnificent buildings along the streets.
</P>
<P>
After the July 1 handover, all 180,000 members of the Hong Kong
civil service will retain their current jobs.
</P>
<P>
"It is a blessing for Hong Kong that the civil service can work
with contentment and a long-term plan," said Hui Kwok-hung, a
public servant.
</P>
<P>
"What I can do for the handover is to do a good job at my
current post," said Wong Kwong-chung, 48, of the Department of
Immigration.
</P>
<P>
With only five days to go before Hong Kong returns to China,
the 6.4 million local residents, while keeping to their normal way
of life, can easily perceive a growing atmosphere of celebration
and festivity when they take a walk in major shopping streets
after a day's work.
</P>
<P>
The glass walls of commercial and office buildings have been
newly decked out with tens of thousands of decorative lights.
</P>
<P>
They feature various kinds of patterns, such as bauhinia, a
flower representing Hong Kong, dragon heads, and Chinese
characters that read "Celebrate Handover '97."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970626.0073 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Before Handover (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
When night falls, these lights start to rival the colorful
neons, adding splendor and a festive atmosphere to the skyline of
Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
"Hong Kong has never been prettier as it is now, when the
handover is arriving," exclaimed a couple of young lovers enjoying
the view on the Peak.
</P>
<P>
For a good observer, there are a lot of new spectacles to see
in the pre-handover Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Along the banks of the Victoria Harbor, nearly 100 commercial
and office buildings have started to hang the Five-Star Red Flag,
China's national flag, the regional flag of the Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region (KKSAR) and banners marking the return of
Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Some large shopping malls have set up special counters that
sell various kinds of handover souvenirs, including gold coins,
stamps, badges, handbags, toys and other articles.
</P>
<P>
Motorcades of the Hong Kong police force can occasionally be
seen roaring across town. They are rehearsing for the reception
and escort of dignitaries who will attend the Hong Kong handover
ceremony at midnight on June 30.
</P>
<P>
There are long queues in front of the mansion of the Department
of Immigration. Waiting patiently in the line are local citizens
applying for a HKSAR passport.
</P>
<P>
The Department of Immigration gave out more than 91,000
application forms on June 10, the first day for the issue of the
form.
</P>
<P>
There are visibly more visitors in the streets than before, who
are easily recognizable by the map they hold.
</P>
<P>
The return of Hong Kong has attracted nearly 10,000 journalists
and a large number of tourists from all over the world, and most
of the local hotels to date have been fully occupied.
</P>
</TEXT>
