<HEADLINE> MNLF Helps Military Fight MILF Rebels in Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Another Muslim armed group was
dragged today into the ongoing conflicts between Moro Islamic
Liberation Front (MILF) rebels and government troops in Mindanao,
the southern Philippines.
</P>
<P>
Nur Misuari, governor of the Autonomous Region of Muslim
Mindanao (ARMM), today ordered the deployment of three battalions
of his Moro National Liberation Front (MNLF) men in North Cotabato
to reinforce the government troops there.
</P>
<P>
Misuari, who is also chairman of the MNLF, said the troop will
help the government troops conduct mop-up operations against the
MILF in Kabacan town in North Cotabato, according to reports of
the local television ABS-CBN.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, some 7,000 armed civilians organized by a private
organization vowed to attack the MILF if the rebel group continued
to launch offensives against the Moro people in the region.
</P>
<P>
Heavy fighting is going on in Kabacan town between the
government troops and some 1,000 Moro Islamic Liberation Front
(MILF) rebels who still held some 40 hostages as human shields.
</P>
<P>
Today's conflict started at 5:30 a.m. when MILF rebels stopped
three buses along a highway in Kabacan and held hostage some 100
passengers.
</P>
<P>
After a four-hour fierce battle, 60 hostages were rescued by
the military. The battle reportedly killed four soldiers, two
civilians and one rebel.
</P>
<P>
But the MILF leadership denied their men took the civilians
hostage, saying those passengers were just caught in cross fire
between the soldiers and the MILF fighters.
</P>
<P>
The highway, linking North Cotabato and Davao province, was
reopened at noon after being closed for six hours due to the
fighting. But local buslines refused to run on the highway unless
the government guarantees their safety.
</P>
<P>
Earlier reports said 47 rebels and at least five soldiers were
killed during the fierce clashes between the MILF and the military
in the past 10 days.
</P>
<P>
The MNLF is a former major Muslim rebel group in the southern
Philippines, which signed a peace deal with the government last
September. The MILF, a breakaway group of the MNLF, refused to
accept the peace deal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
