<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Favors Gradual Ban on Landmines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, June 26 (Xinhua) -- China favors banning
anti-personnnel landmines in a step by step manner, rather than an
immediate total ban, China's Ambassador to the Conference on
Disarmament (CD) Sha Zukang said today.
</P>
<P>
But he said China would not object to the appointment of a
special coordinator to try and launch negotiations on a global
landmines ban.
</P>
<P>
Sha said China believed the time was far from ripe for the
prohibition of such a small defensive weapons like anti-personnel
landmines. The CD should concentrate on arms control and
disarmament issues that have a significant impact on international
security and stability.
</P>
<P>
But Sha told the last meeting of the second 1997 session of the
United Nations-sponsored that, "Considering that the overwhelming
majority of CD members demand or are prepared to address the
landmine issue early, the Chinese delegation is willing to show
flexibility."
</P>
<P>
The forum today agreed to appoint a special coordinator who
will try to look into launching talks on banning the use, storage,
production and transfer of landmines.
</P>
<P>
The consensus decision, reached a day before the forum ends its
second session, was a breakthrough in the Geneva talks which have
been deadlocked all year due to a row between Western states eager
to negotiate global bans on landmines and the production of
bomb-making fissile material, and non-aligned states seeking
security and stability.
</P>
<P>
Sha said China was not opposed to the objective of the
prohibition of anti-personnel landmines realized in a phased
approach, but could not agree to any immediate total ban.
</P>
<P>
Both humanitarian concerns and national security
interests should be taken into account when addressing the
landmine issue, he said.
</P>
<P>
The weapons remained an "indispensable, legitimate and
conventional means of national defense" for his vast country which
has long land borders and an "uncertain security environment", Sha
noted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970626.0084 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Return Encourages Macao's Return: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MACAO, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong's coming return offers a
good example and a great encourage to the return of Macao, a top
Chinese official said here in Macao Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Wang Qiren, director of the Xinhua News Agency Macao Bureau,
spoke highly of Hong Kong's return to reporters from Hong Kong,
China's inland areas and Macao.
</P>
<P>
"The successful practice of the 'one country, two systems'
principle in Hong Kong has created valuable experience for the
stable transition and smooth handover of power in Macao," he said,
adding "It means a model, an encouragement and an inspiration to
the return of Macao."
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong's return not only brushes aside the national
humiliation imposed on China over the past 150 years, but also
shows that China has become increasingly stronger and has the
ability in resolving the issue of national reunification, he
said.
</P>
<P>
The concept of "one country, two systems", he said, has
maintained prosperity and stability in Hong Kong. It will also be
of "special significance to the economic growth, social stability
and stable transition in Macao", he noted.
</P>
<P>
The official pointed out that politically, Hong Kong's return
means the first step in China's reunification cause, which will be
followed by the return of Macao. Macao residents will see the
bright future of Macao from the implementation of the "one
country, two systems" in Hong Kong, he said.
</P>
<P>
Economically, Hong Kong's return will increase the economic
cooperation between the two places and it will help Macao's
economic expansion and stability, he noted.
</P>
<P>
"The preparation for Macao's return will enter into a new stage
after Hong Kong's return," he stressed, "Today's Hong Kong will be
tomorrow's Macao. The work is entering a key period as Macao's
return is drawing near."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970626.0085 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Brief on Hong Kong's Return </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Following are the news in brief on
activities and events related to the upcoming return of Hong Kong
to the motherland:
</P>
<P>
Tibetans Hail HK Return
</P>
<P>
Local people and religious leaders and scholars in Lhasa, the
capital of the Tibetan Autonomous Region, held a meeting on
Wednesday to greet the forthcoming return of Hong Kong to the
motherland.
</P>
<P>
The participants said that Hong Kong's return and the
reunification of the motherland are the common aspiration of the
entire Chinese people and any activities to split the country are
contrary to their fundamental interests.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai Broadcast Back-up
</P>
<P>
Qibao Satellite Ground Station has been made an alternative for
Hong Kong's ground station for broadcasting the handover ceremony
live, if necessary.
</P>
<P>
The Shanghai station has spent over 600,000 US dollars to
improve equipment for the purpose. Shanghai has also lent three
vehicles for use with satellite communications to Beijing to help
receive TV broadcasts from Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
The film "Opium War"
</P>
<P>
The film "Opium War", which was shot by the E'mei Film Studio
in Chengdu, the capital of Sichuan Province in Southwest China,
opened in Chengdu recently, and was received well.
</P>
<P>
The film tells the story of the war between China and Britain
that was triggered by Britain's profitable opium trade. After the
war Hong Kong was ceded to Britain.
</P>
<P>
The film is to be distributed in Japan, the Republic of Korea,
Southeast Asian countries, and Europe and North and South America.
</P>
<P>
Card Phone on Train
</P>
<P>
Card phones have been installed on trains 97 and 98 that
operate between Beijing and Hong Kong to meet passengers' demands.
</P>
<P>
The phones are already in use on inter-city luxury passenger
trains in China.
</P>
<P>
Incense Vies For Guiness Record
</P>
<P>
Wang Yuanzhi, a farmer-turned businessman in Anhua County, in
central China's Hunan Province, spent 11,000 yuan to produce a
piece of incense to mark the forthcoming return of Hong Kong to
the motherland.
</P>
<P>
Wang filed papers with various departments to get the Guiness
Book of Records to record his 5.5-m-tall, 3.3-m-in-diameter, and
4.7-cu.m. accomplishment. It is said that the incense can keep
burning for more than two months.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
