<DOCNO> XIE19970626.0086 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Africa Used as Transient Point for Drug </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
(by Wang Jinyu)
</P>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Drug abuse continues to increase
worldwide with African continent increasingly used as a transient
point for drug trafficking, the World Drug Report 1997 says.
</P>
<P>
The report was launched at a press conference held here today
by the Regional Office for Eastern and Southern Africa of the
United Nations International Drug Control Program (UNDCP).
</P>
<P>
The UNDCP said in a press release that cocaine continued to
arrive from South America to Southern Africa and was transported
through the continent to Europe.
</P>
<P>
Heroin is also being shipped from Asia enroute to Europe and
North America through the African continent, said the report
which was issued to mark the 10th anniversary of the
International Day Against Drug Abuse and Illicit Trafficking on
June 26.
</P>
<P>
It pointed out that illicit drugs were also being produced in
Africa with Morocco, South Africa and Lesotho topping the list of
African cannabis producers.
</P>
<P>
Until recently, the report noted, khat produced in east Africa
is perceived as a regional phenomenon but can now be found on the
streets of European cities.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, the production of opium poppy in the
world has more than tripled since 1985 and coca leaf production
has doubled between 1985 and 1994.
</P>
<P>
The illicit production of opium gum throughout the world is
estimated to reach 5,000 tons in 1996 with a third of the total
believed to be consumed as opium.
</P>
<P>
About 1,000 tons of cocaine were manufactured from 300,000
tons of coca leaf produced last year mainly in Peru, Colombia and
Bolivia, the report said.
</P>
<P>
In terms of volume, it stated, the most heavily trafficked
drug in the world is cannabis, and in 1995, 3,000 tons of herbal
cannabis and 1,000 tons of cannabis resin were seized globally.
</P>
<P>
In the same year, cocaine seizures amounted to 251 tons while
31 tons of heroin and 13 tons of morphine were seized the world
over.
</P>
<P>
According to the unofficial UNDCP estimation, the annual
global prevalence rate of illicit drug consumption is likely to
be in the range of 3.3 percent to 4.1 percent of the total
population.
</P>
<P>
The most widely abused drug is cannabis which is consumed by
about 2.5 percent of the world population or about 140 million
people worldwide.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, about 8 million people or 0.14
percent of the global population are taking heroin and at least
13 million people or 0.23 percent of the global population abuse
cocaine.
</P>
<P>
The press release quoted UNDCP Executive Director Giorgio
Giacomelli as saying that the "drug phenomenon is a threat to
every level of society and to international peace and security."
</P>
<P>
Giacomell called on all communities in the world to be
mobilized to prevent drug abuse. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970626.0087 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> hkhk - HK's Imports Up, Domestic Exports Down in May </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 26 (Xinhua) -- The value of Hong Kong's imports
increased over a year earlier, that of the re-exports decreased
marginally while domestic exports continued to decline on a
year-on-year basis, according to the Census and Statistics
Department (CSD).
</P>
<P>
The value of total exports in May 1997 decreased by 0.8 percent
over a year earlier to 117 billion HK dollars (15 billion U.S.
dollars).
</P>
<P>
within total exports, the value of re-exports decreased
marginally by 0.1 percent to 100.2 billion HK dollars (12.8
billion U.S. dollars), while that of domestic exports decreased by
4.5 percent to 16.8 billion HK dollars (2.15 billion U.S.
dollars).
</P>
<P>
The value of imports increased by 3.5 percent in May 1997 over
a year earlier to 134.5 billion HK dollars (17.24 billion U.S.
dollars).
</P>
<P>
As the value of total exports in May 1997 was less than that of
total imports, there was a visible trade deficit of 17.5 billion
HK dollars (2.24 billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
This was larger than the corresponding deficit of 12 billion HK
dollars (1.53 billion U.S. dollars) in May 1996, but it was
smaller than the deficit of 18.1 billion HK dollars (2.32 billion
U.S. dollars), in April 1997.
</P>
<P>
For the first five months of 1997, the value of total exports
increased by 2.0 percent over the same period last year. Among
this, the value of re-exports rose by 3.3 percent while that of
domestic exports decreased by 5.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
The value of imports showed an increase of 4.2 percent. Over
the same period, a visible trade deficit of 83.8 billion HK
dollars (1.07 billion U.S. dollars) was recorded, which is larger
than the deficit of 68.7 billion HK dollars (8.8 billion U.S.
dollars) in the same period in 1996, according to the CSD figures.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
