<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ILO Launches Drive for More Jobs for Women </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, June 26 (Xinhua) -- The International Labor
Organization (ILO) has outlined a program for more and better
jobs for women, ILO Deputy Director General Mary Chinery-Hesse
said here today.
</P>
<P>
"The international program for more and better jobs for women
will be the ILO's specific response to the successful
implementation of the Platform of Action of the fourth World
Conference on Women, and the gender dimensions of the program of
action of the World Summit for Social Development," she said.
</P>
<P>
The program also represents " a concerted effort to reinforce
the ILO's longstanding priorities to promote full employment in
conditions of equality," she said.
</P>
<P>
She said the program would show that more jobs for women did
not mean less jobs for men, but that better jobs benefit both
women and men, and that women's productive and remunerative
employment helped families.
</P>
<P>
She said although women had made inroads into previously male
dominated occupations and breached the grass ceiling, "
quantitative increases in economic participation of women had not
matched by qualitative improvements."
</P>
<P>
"Most women remain disadvantaged relative to men in terms of
unequal opportunities and treatment in the labor market", she
said.
</P>
<P>
She stressed the need to reform the bases of many current
policies and programs to improve women's employment as they did
not represent the realities of today nor the likely future.
</P>
</TEXT>
