<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Southern African States Winning Anti-inflation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Southern African countries,
battling high inflation in their economies, have scored dramatic
successes in the past few months due to a generally good
agricultural season across the region, the Zimbabwe News Agency
reported today.
</P>
<P>
Former hyper-inflation-ridden economies of Mozambique, Zambia
and Malawi have all recorded a sustained deceleration in
inflation, with Malawi's annual rate dropping to 7.2 percent last
April from a high of 80 percent two years ago.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe, which has seen its inflation rate rised to above 20
percent recently, is still to record a sustained deceleration in
the rate of increase in prices to the extent achieved by its
neighbors.
</P>
<P>
Mozambique's rate of inflation, defined as a sustained
increase in the prices of goods in 1994, was pegged at 70.2
percent, but latest figures from the National Statistics Board
shows a sharp drop ranging from 15.3 percent in Maputo to 19
percent in the northern city of Nampula.
</P>
<P>
While the sharp fall in inflation has been attributed to the
excellent harvest in 1996, the stabilization of the Mozambican
Metical and the fall in the South African Rand resulted in the
fall in prices of imports from South Africa.
</P>
<P>
Zambia, relentlessly pursuing economic reforms, also has
something to show for its perseverance with latest figures
showing that inflation now averages 19 percent.
</P>
<P>
At one time inflation in the copper-producing country was
galloping at 200 percent.
</P>
<P>
Zambia and Malawi have taken tough measures to reduce public
spending with Zambia selling off almost all public enterprises
while Malawi has introduced a cash budget, spending only
according to revenue realized. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
