<HEADLINE> China Making Great Effort To Fight Drought </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Vice-Premier Jiang Chunyun,
speaking to a televised meeting held by the State Council today,
called on many parts of the country to take immediate steps to
fight drought to protect the next harvest.
</P>
<P>
By June 23, droughts had hit 17.3 million ha of crops, 58
million of which were hit severely.
</P>
<P>
Weather forecasters say that in late June most parts of north
China will have less rainfall, while the middle and lower reaches
of the Yangtze River, China's longest, will probably suffer from
a summer drought, Jiang warned.
</P>
<P>
More than 20 million people are working daily in the nationwide
drought relief campaign, and have managed to irrigate or preserve
soil moisture on four million ha of drought-stricken crops.
</P>
<P>
But much remains in the drought-relief work, as the drought
gets worse, and because of the arrival of summer planting, a
greater effort must be made to plant as much as is possible, he
urged.
</P>
<P>
Harvests and increases in farmers' income are important to
China's reforms, development, and stability, and people must put
their heart into this work, he said.
</P>
<P>
People in some areas were overjoyed by the summer harvest, and
are still counting heavily on good weather. But something must be
done to show them just severe the drought is, and how to make the
most of limited water resources for summer planting, he said.
</P>
<P>
A better job must be done in purchasing grains. Unauthorized
charges or getting funds from farmers must be strictly prohibited
to lessen their burden, and the land contract policy will remain
unchanged for another 30 years. Those who violate the regulations
will be punished, he emphasized. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
