<HEADLINE> U.S. Offers Credit for Jordan's Small Business </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, June 26 (Xinhua) -- The United States signed a
agreement here today with the Jordanian government to provide the
kingdom with some 5 million U.S. dollars for its broad-based
economic projects, especially small business projects, Radio
Jordan reported.
</P>
<P>
The money is part of the 100 million dollars extra credit for
Jordan announced recently by U.S. President Bill Clinton, who
also pledged a year ago to offer Jordan 300 million dollars
worth of military aid during his second term of office.
</P>
<P>
The accord was signed at the Ministry of Planning by Rima
Khalaf, Jordanian minister of planning, and Lewis Lark,
director of the U.S. Agency for International Development in
Jordan.
</P>
<P>
The agreement aims to provide the Jordanians with bigger
access to financial services, particularly credit services for
operation of small businesses, including women entrepreneurs and
owners of small business in isolated regions of the kingdom.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the objective of the agreement is to encourage the
implementation of policy reforms that will help increase
investment and trade and in effect expand economic opportunities
for the Jordanians.
</P>
<P>
Jordan is now carrying out an economic reform program that is
structured by the International Monetary Fund and due to end in
1999. 
</P>
