<HEADLINE> Suspected Drug Dealer Ordered to Be Extradited </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 25 (Xinhua) -- A court in Mombasa, the biggest
port city in Kenya, has ordered a suspected Dutch international
drug trafficker extradited to the United States to answer to
charges of trafficking in 65 tons of hashish.
</P>
<P>
Two U.S. marshalls are due to arrive in Kenya to collect the
Dutchman, identified as Wouter van Frassen, local press reported
today.
</P>
<P>
The court order came on Wednesday after the Netherlands'
government withdrew its extradition claim on the suspect.
</P>
<P>
Frassen was arrested together with four Indonisian nationals
on May 13 aboard a vessel carrying about 65 tons of hashish off
African coast to the U.S. in April, 1996, said the report quoting
John Burns, an agent from the U.S. Drug Enforcement
Administration.
</P>
<P>
John Burns also provided with evidence that the Dutchman has
been trafficking in narcotic drug between Far East countries,
Africa coast and America.
</P>
<P>
Frassen was approached by a drug baron in early 1995 to
transport a large quantity of hashish from the African coast to
the U.S., said Burns.
</P>
<P>
Burns said his agency has established that Frassen is a drug
trafficker after thorough investigations which include monitoring
his telephone conversations and business records. 
</P>
</TEXT>
