<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan Asks Russia to Probe Shooting Near Disputed Islands </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Japan's Foreign Ministry today asked
the Russian government to investigate whether Russian coast guards
were involved in a shooting incident near the dispute Habomai
Island in which two Japanese fishermen were injured.
</P>
<P>
Japanese officials from the Maritime Safety Agency (MSA) said
that an unidentified ship fired on the 4.7-ton Japanese fishing
boat, with three crewmen on board, in waters near the Habomai
island late on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The MSA has not yet been able to confirm the nationality of the
ship which opened fire and the Russian side has not yet responded
to Japan's inquiries.
</P>
<P>
Last August, Russian patrol boats fired on two Japanese fishing
vessels in waters near the Habomai island, injuring two crewmen.
</P>
<P>
Habomai and three other Russian-held islands, located northeast
of Japan's main northern island of Hokkaido, were taken by the
Soviet Red Army in the last days of World War II. Japan has
refused to sign a World War II peace treaty with Moscow without
the return of the islands.
</P>
<P>
Russia has repeatedly accused Japanese fishing boats of
poaching in Russian waters and the two countries have held several
rounds of talks since March 1995 to try and resolve the dispute
over the safety of Japanese fishing boats near the islands.
</P>
</TEXT>
