<DOCNO> XIE19970626.0107 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Warns Youths to Stay Away From Drugs (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Shenzhen Compulsory Rehabilitation Center is supposed to be
the best in the country. Two-thirds of the addicts are university
and middle school students and unemployed young people.
</P>
<P>
According to staff members, young people aged 12 to 25
accounted for 59 percent of the 6,000 addicts undergoing
rehabilitation in the center from 1991 to 1996.
</P>
<P>
When explaining why young people are easy victims, Zhou
Liqiang, an expert at the center, told the reporter that young
people are full of curiosity and it is difficult for them to tell
right from wrong without sufficient education, and the main reason
is that they have no information at all about the harm of drug
addiction.
</P>
<P>
According to Zhou, most schools have paid little attention to
providing young students with information about narcotics because
the number of drug addicts is still quite small.
</P>
<P>
"Schools should be in charge of students' actions when they
enter society," Zhou commented, meaning that they should be
educated about the evils of drugs.
</P>
<P>
He also suggested that students be organized to visit some
rehabilitation centers as extra-curricular activities. Parents and
other people should also help educate them about the harm of drug
addiction.
</P>
<P>
To combat trafficking, smuggling, and drug abuse, the Chinese
government is running a nation-wide campaign against drugs from
April to September.  
</P>
</TEXT>
