<HEADLINE> Hong Kong's Foreign Reserves on Rise in May </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong's foreign reserves
increased by three billion U.S. dollars at end of May over the
previous month to 66.6 billion U.S. dollars, according to the
latest figures issued by the Hong Kong Monetary Authority (HKMA)
today.
</P>
<P>
A HKMA spokesman attributed the increase to seasonal increases
in government placements of fiscal reserves with the Exchange
Fund.
</P>
<P>
He said that the above figures excluded forward transactions
yet to be settled. Including forward transactions, the foreign
reserves reached 68.4 billion U.S. dollars at the end of May, as
against 67.6 billion U.S. dollars at the end of April, he added.
</P>
<P>
At present, Hong Kong's foreign reserves ranked in the seventh
place in the world next to the United States. 
</P>
