<DOCNO> XIE19970626.0110 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Drug Abuse on Rise in Nepal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Drug abuse and trafficking in
this Himalayan Kingdom of Nepal has been on rise in recent years,
leading to an increase in theft, pickpocketing, use of fatal
weapons and other crimes.
</P>
<P>
Though the history of drug abuse is quite short in Nepal, it is
spreading its clutches at an alarming rate.
</P>
<P>
There are three forms of drug crime in the country, namely
addiction, trafficking and production, Nepali Home Ministry
officials said.
</P>
<P>
The number of drug addicts have doubled in the country in the
past six years to about 50,000, with 10 percent of them being
women.
</P>
<P>
Figures also show that during the 11 months from July 1996 to
May 1997, the police have seized 3,889 kg of marijuana, hashish
and heroin.
</P>
<P>
The number of those arrested on charges of drug abuse and
trafficking increased from 56 in 1982 to 725 in 1996, and a total
of 6,676 persons have been arrested on the same charges in the
past 17 years, according to figures provided by the Narcotic
Control Division (NCD) of the Home Ministry.
</P>
<P>
The number of addicts using hemp, hashish and heroin is
decreasing, while an increasing number of them are turning to
narcotic tablets, injections and phensedyl since 1991, said the
NCD.
</P>
<P>
In Nepal, most of the addicts begin by taking oral tablets and
then move over to intravenous (IV) drugs. Because of the sharing
of syringes, IV drugs are especially harmful and risky.
</P>
<P>
Out of the 637 AIDS patients in Nepal, 12 were found to be drug
addicts. Even worse, the majority of the drug addicts had donated
blood, a research said.
</P>
<P>
Drug abuse is now poised as a serious social problem in Nepal.
</P>
<P>
Police officials said that 13 percent of pickpockets are drug
users, 5 percent of theft are related to drug abuse, which is also
blamed for such crimes as hooliganism and use of fatal weapons.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, the Nepali government has taken sorts of
measures to curb the rising trend of drug abuse in the country.
</P>
<P>
The Narcotics Control Act 1988 has specifically banned the
selling of some medicines which can lead to addiction without the
doctors' prescription.
</P>
<P>
In 1995, the Nepali government began to implement a program for
drug control in cooperation with the United Nations Drug Control
Program (UNDCP), involving police, custom officers and social
workers.
</P>
<P>
Currently the government is implementing a narcotic control
master plan prepared with the cooperation of UNDCP in 1992.
</P>
<P>
Under the plan, efforts are being made to control illegal
production, trafficking, peddling and abuse of narcotics.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the police has launched a drug abuse control and
rehabilitation program that aims to bring under control the number
of drug addicts and illegal trade in drugs in the Kathmandu
Valley, home to the majority of drug addicts in Nepal.
</P>
<P>
Despite these efforts, illegal hemp cultivation still exists in
the southern and some other parts of the country.
</P>
<P>
And the relapse rate in Nepal is as high as 99 percent.
</P>
<P>
Observers noted the cruxes lie in this important fact that much
of the ongoing measures are of a short-term nature. In order to
produce the desired outcome, measures need to be sustained over
the long haul through greater commitment and patience based on an
increased sense of collective responsibility.
</P>
<P>
The fact that there is not a proper rehabilitation center for
drug addicts in Nepal may also help explain why drug addiction is
on rise.
</P>
<P>
Yet, public awareness against drug abuse is thought to be
essential to control drug addiction.
</P>
<P>
To this end, the International Day Against Drug Abuse and
Trafficking is observed Thursday throughout Nepal.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970626.0111 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Future of Hong Kong Aviation Promising, Says Boeing Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 26 (Xinhua) -- The president of Boeing China
predicted today that there would be even greater expansion of Hong
Kong's aviation industry after the region returns to the
motherland on July 1.
</P>
<P>
There will be more commercial opportunities in China, said Mike
Zimmerman, who noted that the past, present, and future of Hong
Kong "goes hand in hand" with commercial aviation.
</P>
<P>
Zimmerman pointed out that China will have the fastest air
travel growth of any region in the world, with benefits for the
Hong Kong Special Administrative Region as a consequence, because
it is "central to the country's international trade, banking, and
other dealings with the world."
</P>
<P>
China represents a tenth of the 1.1-trillion-US-dollar market
for new airplanes in the world for the next two decades, with more
than 1,900 new jets needed, he said. And the new airport at Chek
Lap Kok in Hong Kong will further consolidate Hong Kong's position
as Asia's premier aviation hub.
</P>
<P>
He said that jets with a single aisle will grow in importance
in China, and represent more than 70 percent of all deliveries
over the next 20 years.
</P>
<P>
"Countless new point-to-point aviation services between the
China's inland area and Hong Kong will be inaugurated with 737
and 757 airplanes," said Zimmerman. "Later, as these markets
mature, they can be served with 767s or even 777s," he added.
</P>
<P>
With 737s already accounting for 60 percent of all jet aircraft
delivered to China, the next generation of 737 offers more for
operators looking to expand into the Chinese market, he told
Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
Zimmerman said that a fourth type of the Boeing 737 is
currently being evaluated. The 737-900X is a twinjet that will
seat up to 178 passengers in two classes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
