<HEADLINE> Works of Art Mark Return of Hong Kong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 26 (Xinhua) -- A long scroll painting and a large
statue have been completed in the cities of Beijing and Shenzhen
to greet the return of Hong Kong to the motherland on July 1.
</P>
<P>
The "Picture of the Great Wall" was painted on a 360-meter-long
scroll by Sun Yingdong, a 55-year-old artist at the Beijing Youth
Film Studio.
</P>
<P>
"The painting expresses my joyous feelings about the return of
Hong Kong to the motherland," said the artist, who took 14 months
to paint 99 scenes from the Great Wall on the paper roll.
</P>
<P>
The statue, "A Sail Returning from the Sea", is 19.97 meters
high and is made of white marble. It was carved at the end of the
Luohu Bridge in Shenzhen, near Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese characters for "return", inlaid with gold, is
carved on the sail. On the four-meter-high pedestal are bronze
castings about the history of Hong Kong, from being ceded to
Britain to its return to the Motherland.
</P>
<P>
The statue, which is valued at four million yuan (about 482,000
US dollars), will be unveiled on July 1. 
</P>
</TEXT>
