<HEADLINE> Saudi's Crown Prince Arrives in Lebanon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Saudi Crown Prince Abdullah Ibn
Abdul-Aziz arrived in Lebanon this afternoon on a visit, the first
by a Saudi royal member since 1975 when Lebanese 15-year civil war
erupted.
</P>
<P>
The crown prince, with his 140-member entourage, came to
Lebanon by land from a two-day visit to Damascus and was received
on the Lebanese-Syrian border by Lebanese Prime Minister Rafik
Al-Hariri.
</P>
<P>
During his three-day visit, Abdullah will have meetings with
Lebanese President Elias Hrawi, Hariri, House Speaker Nabih Berri
and will inspect some projects of reconstruction in Beirut.
</P>
<P>
Hariri has hailed the landmark visit of Saudi crown prince
as an enormous boost to Lebanon's reconstruction drive and a
display of the strong bond between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Opening a weekly cabinet session Wednesday night, the Lebanese
prime minister noted that Abdullah's visit to Syria and Lebanon
comes at a particularly critical time when Israel continues
to occupy the Arab land and the Israeli-Turkish security pact
pose threat to the Arab world.
</P>
<P>
A military training agreement signed by Turkey and Israel in
February 1996 generated fear in Middle East countries that Turkey
was aligning itself with the Jewish state against Arab countries.
</P>
<P>
Hariri added the visit is of "utmost importance to Lebanon as
it reflects Saudi Arabia's keen interest in our causes."
</P>
<P>
He spoke highly of Saudi Arabia's contribution to Lebanon's
reconstruction drive through grants and donations that have
topped 500 million U.S. dollars in the past few years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
