<HEADLINE> New Use of Kai Tak Airport in Hong Kong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 26 (Xinhua) -- The Kai Tak International
Airport in Hong Kong will be built into a new town for 300,000
residents after the new airport opens in Chek Lap Kok in 1998.
</P>
<P>
Relevant departments in Hong Kong are drawing up plans to gear
this prime area with the project to fill up the sea in the Kowloon
Bay, Leung Po-wing, secretary for Planning Environment and Lands,
said today.
</P>
<P>
With the progress of the sea filling-up project, large-scale
construction will begin in the year 2001, so that residents will
be able to move in before the year 2006, he said.
</P>
<P>
Because of the location of the Kai Tak airport, construction
planning and development in Kowloon have long been restricted.
</P>
<P>
In future, the whole Kowloon Bay including the site of the Kai
Tak Airport will be used mainly for construction of high-density
buildings, such as residential quarters, office buildings and
commercial facilities.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, proper arrangements will also be made for the
construction of parks and transportation facilities, the official
said, adding that a small area will be used to develop
pollution-free industries.
</P>
<P>
In early 1998, the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region
Government will announce an overall plan for construction in the
Kowloon Bay for public discussion.
</P>
<P>
An official with the Hong Kong Tourist Association said that
after the closure of the Kai Tak Airport, the 280 ha of land
vacated plus the 300 ha secured from sea filling up will make it
possible to build a number of new scenic spots and tourism
facilities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
