<HEADLINE> Britain Urges Germany not to Pull out of Eurofighter Project </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Britain has urged Germany not to pull
out of their joint project with Italy and Spain to build a new
type of jet fighter, Eurofighter.
</P>
<P>
Germany's withdrawal "would deal a blow to all our efforts to
strengthen the European space and aviation industry against
growing competition from the United States," said British Defense
Secretary George Robertson in an interview with the German daily
Bild Zeitung.
</P>
<P>
The German government is said to be reviewing its role in the
65 billion U.S.-dollar scheme in a bid to cut state spending so as
to ensure that it meets the membership criteria for the planned
single European currency.
</P>
<P>
Bonn is expected to announce on July 11, as part of its 1998
budget, whether it will take part in the Eurofighter project.
</P>
<P>
Reports said that Britain, Italy and Spain have already
approved the project and plan to buy 232, 121 and 87 Eurofighters
respectively. The German armed forces intended to buy 180
fighters at a cost of about 23 billion marks (about 13.6 billion
dollars). 
</P>
</TEXT>
