<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Per Capita Income Up in Kenya, Uganda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Kenya and Uganda have both
improved their position in the latest World Bank Development
report indicators of the world's poorest nations but per capita
income in Tanzania has fallen again.
</P>
<P>
Per capita income in Kenya has risen to 280 U.S. Dollars,
making the eastern African country for the first time in five
years no longer amongst the poorest 20 countries in the world,
the "Daily Nation" newspaper quoted the report as saying today.
</P>
<P>
Ugandans have also seen their per capita income rising for the
sixth consecutive year to 240 Dollars, and for the first time
since 1980s the country is not amongst the poorest 10 countries
in the world, said the report issued in London recently.
</P>
<P>
Mozambique is again the poorest country in the world according
to the 1997 report with a per capita income of only 80 Dollars.
It is followed by Ethiopia with a per capita income of 100
Dollars and Tanzania with 120 Dollars.
</P>
<P>
Sixteen of the world's poorest 20 states remain in sub-Saharan
Africa, while 12 of the richest 20 are in Europe.
</P>
<P>
The richest country in sub-Saharan Africa is South Africa with
a per capita income of 3,160 Dollars, followed by Botswana (3,020
Dollars) and Namibia (2,000 Dollars).
</P>
<P>
Only these three sub-Saharan African countries have per capita
incomes greater than 1,000 Dollars.
</P>
<P>
The richest country in the world is Switzerland whose per
capita income hits 40,630 Dollars, followed by Japan with 39,640
Dollars and Norway with 31,250 Dollars.
</P>
<P>
The United States is rated the sixth richest country in the
world with Britain the 18th. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
