<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-26 12:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UNSCOM's New Chief Assures Objectivity to Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, June 26 (Xinhua) -- The new chief of the U.N. Special
Commission (UNSCOM) on Iraq has assured Iraq that he will be
"objective" in his work related to the inspection missions.
</P>
<P>
The official Iraqi News Agency reported today that Richard
Rutler, who is to replace the present UNSCOM chief Rolf Ekeus on
July 1, made the promise Wednesday at a meeting in New York with
Iraqi deputy Prime Minister Tareq Aziz.
</P>
<P>
Rutler said that his efforts to be objective will be based on
cooperation with Iraq to solve the problem of eliminating weapons
of mass destruction in Iraq, including ballistic missiles,
biological and chemical weaponry.
</P>
<P>
The UNSCOM's new chief said he is happy with his first meeting
with Aziz, who is on a visit to the U.N. Aziz also expressed his
happiness to work with Rutler, saying that Iraq will cooperate
fully with the UNSCOM.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has been accusing Ekeus of taking a "biased" stance
towards it and said that he is a politician rather than a
U.N. official. Its denial of the entry of U.N. inspectors into
chosen sites has prompted the Security Council to threaten with
tougher sanctions.
</P>
<P>
Rutler, Australia's U.N. ambassador, was appointed early in May
as the new executive chairman of the UNSCOM.
</P>
<P>
Iraq is not allowed to have weapons of mass destruction,
including missiles with ranges beyond 150 kilometers, after its
troops were defeated by the U.S.-led allied forces in the 1991
Gulf War triggered by its invasion of Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
The UNSCOM in charge of scrapping the weapons suspects Iraq
still possesses a considerable number of the missiles. However,
Baghdad denies concealing any such weapons. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970626.0125 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Warns Youths to Stay Away From Drugs (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 26 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese government is looking
for more effective ways and various activities to teach young
people to stay away from drugs.
</P>
<P>
The aim of the nation-wide campaign is to increase young
people's ability to avoid drug addiction and to fight drug
abuse. The National Narcotics Control Committee (NNCC) says that
since June, millions of schoolboys and girls in urban and rural
areas of south China's Guangdong, Fujian and Yunnan provinces have
held anti-narcotics demonstrations, and many students have taken
an oath to fight drug addiction.
</P>
<P>
Sources say that the majority of colleges and middle and
primary schools have put drug education at their list of programs
and gave students classes on narcotics before the end of the
spring semester.
</P>
<P>
Drug addiction has been avoided in China for more than 30
years, but with the growth in international drug smuggling and
sales, it has begun to reappear in recent years.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Public Security says that the number of
reported or registered drug abusers in China in 1995 was 520,000,
but experts estimate that the real figure is much larger.
</P>
<P>
A NNCC report shows that drug addicts have been found in about
70 percent of China's cities and counties, and that the majority
are young people.
</P>
<P>
"It was because of ignorance that I first touched drugs. If we
had been educated about the evils of drugs, I wouldn't have become
addicted," a 16-year-old addict who declined to give her name told
the reporter at a rehabilitation center in Shenzhen, China's first
special economic zone, in Guangdong Province.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
