<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bonn Strikes Deal to Sell Telecom Stake </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, June 26 (Xinhua) -- The German government is to sell 25
percent of its remaining stake in the German telecom giant
Deutsche Telekom to help meet membership targets for joining the
planned single European currency, the Euro, the government
announced today.
</P>
<P>
Under a deal reached between the government and the Telekom on
Thursday, the shares are to be transferred to the state-owned Bank
for Reconstruction in 1997 and 1998. The move is expected to
generate 25 billion German marks (14.5 billion U.S. dollars) for
the financially strapped government.
</P>
<P>
The two sides also agreed that the shares would not be
permitted to be sold on the stock exchange before the year 2000, a
promise made by the government when the Telekom first went public
in November 1996.
</P>
<P>
However, the Telekom would be allowed to offer parts of the
shares to "strategic investors" in the telecommunications industry.
</P>
<P>
Telekom Chairman Ron Sommer told a general meeting of
shareholders Thursday that the deal would help the company develop
as "a global player on the world market" by increasing its
flexibility.
</P>
<P>
Bonn currently holds about 74 percent of the Telekom
shares. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
