<HEADLINE> Malaysia, Philippines to Enhance Cooperation in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia and the Philippines
plan to enhance their student exchange program in a bid to improve
the educational cooperation between the two countries, Philippine
Education, Culture and Sports Secretary Ricardo Gloria said today.
</P>
<P>
The program to be known as "sisterhood" or "homestay" would be
implemented this year at secondary school level, he told
reporters after a meeting with Malaysian Acting Prime Minister
Anwar Ibrahim here.
</P>
<P>
"The program package is being worked out," Gloria said, who is
here as head of a three-member delegation on a four-day visit to
Malaysia in his capacity as president of the Southeast Asian
Ministers' of Education Council (SEAMIEC).
</P>
<P>
Priority would be given to educational programs before both
countries branch out to other fields such as culture, arts and
technology, he said.
</P>
<P>
According to Gloria, Malaysia and the Philippines also proposed
to have exchange programs for teachers and principals to learn
more about teaching techniques and approaches.
</P>
<P>
As SEAMIEC president, Gloria hoped the program would be
expanded to other Southeast Asian countries.
</P>
<P>
He said the governments of the Southeast Asian countries should
invest more in education, particularly in science, mathematics and
English subjects as the three subjects, in his view, were the most
vital "tools" to compete in the global education system.
</P>
<P>
He said he discussed with Anwar ways to improve educational
programs among Asian countries. 
