<HEADLINE> Nigerian Banker Calls for Bigger Notes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, June 26 (Xinhua) -- A leading Nigerian bank has called
for the introduction of bigger currency notes to reduce the risks
and inconvenience associated with large-scale cash movement.
</P>
<P>
Michel Accad, Managing Director of the Nigeria International
Bank, made the call last week at the
June monthly meeting of the Money Market Association in Lagos.
</P>
<P>
Whereas the biggest note is 50 Naira (less than 60 U.S. Cents)
at the moment, the banker advised the introduction of 500 and
1,000-Naira notes.
</P>
<P>
Turning down the saying that introduction of
high-denomination notes will worsen the inflation situation,
Accad said, "The
only reliable check on inflation is fiscal and monetary
discipline."
</P>
<P>
The manager of a Lagos-based merchant bank supported Accad's
view of point. He urged the central bank to take actions to save
traders who are forced to carry large sum of cash in transacting
businesses.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria now uses notes of 50, 20, 10 and five-Naira, while an
ordinary business transaction is likely to involve tens of
thousands of Naira. It is a common thing to see people carrying
cash in sacks in Nigerian banks just to pay their phone bills.
</P>
</TEXT>
