<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-26 12:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran, Afghanistan on Ending Afghan Civil War </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, June 26 (Xinhua) -- The ousted Afghan president
Burhanuddin Rabbani has discussed with an Iranian envoy on ways of
ending the ongoing Afghan crisis, an official report said here
today.
</P>
<P>
However, the official news agency IRNA gave no specific time or
place of the said meeting because, as an IRNA editor contacted by
phone put it, of "security reasons."
</P>
<P>
Observers here held that the meeting between Rabbani and the
Iraian envoy took place shortly after the talks between Iranian
President Hashemi Rafsanjani and Pakistani Prime Minister Nawaz
Sharif on June 17.
</P>
<P>
However, it remains unknown what kind of agreement, if any,
Rafsanjani and Sharif have reached in their meeting mainly
focusing on the protracted civil war in Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
Islamabad and Tehran are at odds over their support for rival
Afghan factions. Iran accuses Pakistan of supporting the Taliban
which has already controlled 90 percent of the territory in
Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan is believed to have been wielding influence on the
Taliban and wants to consolidate its strategic position in
Afghanistan and expand its influence to Central Asian countries.
</P>
<P>
However, Iran has suffered a big blow since Kabul fell into the
hands of Taliban and Rabbani, who has had the support of Tehran,
was driven northward last September.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian envoy, Alla'eddin Boroujerdi, who is deputy foreign
minister for Asia-Pacific Affairs, discussed with Rabbani the
latest developments in Afghanistan, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
Rabbani was quoted as saying that that Afghan Islamic
government was for restoration of peace and creation of an
atmosphere of mutual understanding in Afghanistan and would
strongly and decisively surpress any measure adopted against the
country.
</P>
<P>
He also condemned blatant support of "certain foreign
countries" for the Taliban, which groups Islamic student
militants, falling short of accusing Pakistan, Saudi Arabia and
the United States.
</P>
<P>
He regarded "alien intervention as the main factor behind
Afghan crisis" and said that the Afghan Moslem government wants to
see an immediate end to the present foreign interference in the
war-torn country.
</P>
<P>
He added that Iran respected all Afghan tribes, including
Pashtuns, Tajikis, Uzbeks and Hezares, believing that each should
have a role in the formation of a popular Islamic government in
the country.
</P>
<P>
Boroujerdi said that Iran is ready to offer any kind of help
to the Afghan Moslem nation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
