<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> hkhk - One Country, Two Monetary Systems After July 1: HK Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong and China's inland
areas will implement the principle of one country, two currencies
and two monetary systems in handling their monetary relations
after July 1, a senior Hong Kong monetary official said here
today.
</P>
<P>
Joseph Yam, chief executive of the Hong Kong Monetary Authority
(HKMA), said at a media briefing: "We have been working closely
with the Chinese authorities to define even more clearly the
monetary relations between Hong Kong and the inland areas of China
under the concept of "one country, two systems" and within the
legal framework laid down in the Basic Law."
</P>
<P>
Speaking of Hong Kong's monetary arrangements through 1997, Yam
told some 100 local and overseas journalists: "'One country, two
systems' means one country, two currencies and two monetary
systems,"
</P>
<P>
"Each other's currency will continue to be considered as
foreign currency. In other word, the Hong Kong dollar is treated
as a foreign currency in the inland areas and the Renminbi, a
foreign currency in Hong Kong," said the chief executive of the
HKMA, which acts as the de facto central bank of Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
The Basic Law states that the Hong Kong dollar, as the legal
tender in the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (HKSAR),
shall continue to circulate, and shall remain freely convertible.
</P>
<P>
It stipulates that the HKSAR government shall provide an
appropriate economic and legal environment for the maintenance of
the status of Hong Kong as an international financial center.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the HKSAR Government shall, on its own, formulate
monetary and financial policies, safeguard the free operation of
financial business and financial markets, and regulate and
supervise them in accordance with law.
</P>
<P>
"The two currencies and the two corresponding monetary systems
are of equal importance to China. One is not subsidiary to the
other and they are to be mutually independent," said the Hong Kong
official.
</P>
<P>
On the relationship between the two monetary authorities -- the
HKMA and the People's Bank of China (PBOC), Yam said: "They are to
be mutually independent. This is demonstrated by the fact that
both the HKMA and the PBOC are members of a number of central
banking forums and institutions, such as the Bank of International
Settlement and the Asia Development Bank."
</P>
<P>
As the economies of Hong Kong and the inland areas are becoming
more integrated, there is obviously a need for greater cooperation
on the monetary front, said the HKMA's chief executive.
</P>
<P>
He noted that after July 1, Hong Kong-based financial
institutions funded by the inland areas must abide by Hong Kong
laws and will not enjoy any privilege.
</P>
<P>
He believed that Hong Kong and the inland areas can join forces
in supervising financial institutions and maintaining currency
stability in Hong Kong. "There is a complementary and mutually
reinforcing relationship," said Yam.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970626.0149 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-26 11:25 </DATE_TIME>
