<HEADLINE> Strong Earthquake Jolts East Iran Again </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, June 26 (Xinhua) -- An earthquake measuring 6.2 degrees
on the Richter scale jolted Qa'en region, about 800 kilometers
east of the capital, the state-run Tehran Radio reported.
</P>
<P>
The report said that the quake occurred at 9.25 a.m. local time
(04:55 GMT) this morning in the eastern Khorasan province.
</P>
<P>
No casualties have been reported so far, though the damages to
the villages that survived previous tremors in this area appeared
to be extensive.
</P>
<P>
Iran's Headquarters for Natural Disasters dispatched its relief
workers and experts to the quake-stricken area this morning to
help the people and assess the damage, according to the radio.
</P>
<P>
The tremor was an aftershock of the 7.1 degree magnitude quake
which hit Birjand and Qa'en on May 10 and claimed about 2,400
lives.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian government has already allocated funds for the
reconstruction of those areas, and pledged new quake-resistant
homes to be built in the quake-prone regions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
