<DOCNO> XIE19970626.0150 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> hkhk - Interview: HK's Civil Service Ranks Are Stable, Says Administrator </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
by Zhou Zongxin
</P>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 26 (Xinhua) -- "A smooth transition is coming
without any problem and we're all confident of Hong Kong's
future," said Lam Woon-kwong, Hong Kong's Secretary for the Civil
Service in a recent interview with Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
After 23 years' service in the govornment and now as head of
the Civil Service Branch, Lam oversees matters concerning the
180,000 people directly employed by the Hong Kong government --
from their employment, promotion, punishment to retirement.
</P>
<P>
Lam has been appointed Secretary for the Civil Service for the
Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (HKSAR) by China's central
government.
</P>
<P>
"The civil servants' ranks are very stable now," Lam said,
citing only four percent of the civil servants having left the
ranks during the past 12 months, which represents the lowest rate
in eight years.
</P>
<P>
"With just days left before the handover, government
departments are operating normally and steadily. The civil
servants at various levels are in a fairly good mental state," Lam
said.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong's highly successful civil service system features
three major characteristics, Lam said.
</P>
<P>
The criterion for recruiting new civil servants is that they
should be talented and capable, and their selection is through a
public application process.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong's civil servants receive fairly high pay, which works
to guard against corruption and talent drainage.
</P>
<P>
And a highly efficient system and the order of law are adopted
for their management, Lam said.
</P>
<P>
The Civil Service Branch is the government department
responsible for working out and revising the system, policies and
regulations governing the management of civil servants.
</P>
<P>
Lam cited a strict and systematized management network as one
of the three major factors behind the stable status of civil
service ranks.
</P>
<P>
The two other factors are Hong Kong's fast economic progress
during the past decades, which has made possible high pay for
civil servants, and an increased watch-dog function played by
community and media, according to Lam.
</P>
<P>
He said these factors are expected to be further strengthened
after the handover. "The Basic Law has laid down articles with
clear and unequivocal wording on ensuring Hong Kong's civil
service system. As China's economy enjoys prosperity, a bright
future can be foreseen for Hong Kong's development and financial
status in the future," Lam said.
</P>
<P>
"And the Basic Law provides that freedom of speech and of the
press shall be maintained as well. So, to draw a reasonable
inference from all these analyses, we are fairly confident of the
future," said Lam.
</P>
<P>
"From the preparatory process for the establishment of the SAR
government, especially after the appoinment of Tung Chee Hwa as
the SAR's Chief Executive, the central government has given him
full confidence and trust," he said.
</P>
<P>
"This has greatly strengthened our confidence in the principle
of 'One Country, Two Systems' and 'Hong Kong people governing Hong
Kong'," Lam added.
</P>
<P>
Lam, who has visited most parts of the Chinese mainland
including Tibet since 1978, encourages his colleagues for such
visits so as to know more about the rest of China. "Seeing is
believing. Our country has changed so fast that you can know this
better and deeper only when you are there," he said.
</P>
<P>
Born in Hong Kong in 1951, Lam joined the Administrative
Service
in 1974 after graduating from the University of Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
He was appointed Deputy Director of Regional Services in 1989,
Deputy Secretary for Civil Service, Civil Service Branch in 1991,
Deputy Secretary for Education and Manpower, Education and
Manpower Branch in 1993 and Director of Education in 1994.
</P>
<P>
Lam took up the current post of Secretary for Civil Service in
February 1996.
</P>
<P>
He was married in 1978 but has no children.
</P>
<P>
Lam's hobbies include reading, traveling and movies. He is a
soccer fan but has not watched local competitions since the
retirement of his favorite player Wong Man-wai in the 1980s.
"Hong Kong soccer needs star players," he said.
</P>
<P>
But he manages never to miss World Cup finals, especially
championship finals. He would enjoy both live broadcast and
tape-recorded
programs over and over again. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970626.0151 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
