<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Manchurian Tigers Thrive In Central China Zoo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZHENGZHOU, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Zoo keepers in charge of
Manchurian tigers at Shangqiu Zoo, in central China's Henan
Province, are celebrating the recent arrival of ten healthy cubs.
</P>
<P>
The births, to three Manchurian tigers, is the latest chapter
in the zoo's tiger-breeding success story. Over the last decade,
68 cubs have been born to these big rare cats, indigenous but
endangered in northeast China. Some 80 percent of the new
arrivals have survived.
</P>
<P>
Manchurian tigers come under the first category of
state-protected animals, and they were previously regarded as
being difficult to breed in captivity. Shangqiu Zoo started to
breed the big cats back in 1968.
</P>
<P>
Wang Tengzhan, director of the zoo, has bred three tigers, and
one of them in turn has given birth to 31 cubs with 24 of them
surviving. The zoo is one of the leading centers for breeding
Manchurian tigers in China. 
</P>
</TEXT>
