<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rising Seas to Flood Cyprus' Coast in 50 Years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus' Larnaca airport and other
low-lying areas of the this eastern Mediterranean island could be
flooded by rising sea water if nothing is to be done to halt
global warming, Cyprus Mail reported today.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted Loizos Hadjioannou, a Cypriot meteorological
service official, as saying that "if pollution continues at the
present rate, and nothing is done to stop it, then, according to
scientific models, a problem with rising sea levels may exist."
</P>
<P>
Hadjioannou said that Larnaca airport, which has an elevation
of just one meter above sea level, could be flooded in about 50
years if scientific predictions proved accurate.
</P>
<P>
Areas like Larnaca bay, at southern coast, Famagusta bay, at
eastern coast and the coast of Paphos of western part of the
island could also face flooding problems, he said.
</P>
<P>
Scientists predict sea levels will rise by between 30 and 100
centimeters over the next century as the planet grows warmer, if
emissions of carbon dioxide and other greenhouse gases are not
reduced.
</P>
<P>
These gases, principally generated by the burning of fossil
fuels like oil and coal, trap the sun's heat, raising global
temperatures and causing polar ice caps to melt releasing water
into the oceans, scientists say.
</P>
<P>
However, Hadjioannou said for Cyprus, sea level rises are a
"future worry".
</P>
<P>
"This matter is not so critical for Cyprus as it is for Indian
Ocean states where whole islands may be inundated," he added.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, Cyprus joined other small island nations at the
U.N. Earth Summit in New York in calling for immediate actions to
halt global warming. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
