<HEADLINE> Options Expiry, Book Squaring Drag Australian Shares </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, June 26 (Xinhua) -- End of the financial year book
squaring and the expiry of June options combined to drag the
Australian share market to a lower close today.
</P>
<P>
Turnover was high as the options expiry coincided with National
Australia Bank Ltd (NAB) going ex-dividend 45 cents and
nervousness ahead of BHP Co Ltd's annual results tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
Australia's current financial year ends on June 30.
</P>
<P>
The all ordinaries index closed 5.2 points down at 2,699.9
while in New York, the Dow Jones industrial average lost 68.1
points to 7,690.0.
</P>
<P>
BHP lost 19 cents to end the day at 19.06 Australian dollars on
turnover of 9.1 million shares ahead of tomorrow's full year
profit results. Analysts have forecast BHP's net profit before
abnormals expected to come in at 1.37 billion Australian dollars
(1.02 billion US dollars) for the year to May 31.
</P>
<P>
Traders said BHP could announce significant write downs as it
starts to account for restructuring designed to put some luster
back into a dull earnings outlook.
</P>
<P>
After the market closed, BHP announced it would sell its
Newcastle-based electrolytic Manganese Dioxide Plant to Delta
Industries electrical Industries Ltd for 42 million US dollars.
</P>
<P>
NAB topped turnover after 26,400 call options were exercised to
purchase 26.4 million shares before the start of trade, dealers
said.
</P>
<P>
More than 30.609 million NAB shares changed hands today worth
376.2 million US dollars.
</P>
<P>
NAB, which went ex-45 cents, closed down 29 cents at 18.68
Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
"NAB did remarkably well to be only down 29, when its dividend
is 45," a broker said.
</P>
<P>
The all industrials index inched 0.4 of a point higher to close
at 4,260.1 while the all resources fell 10.8 to close at 1,495.0.
</P>
<P>
The gold index dipped 5.0 points to 1,456.8 while gold bullion
closed unchanged at 338.10 US dollars an ounce.
</P>
<P>
National turnover totaled 494.53 million shares traded worth
1.861 billion Australian dollars (1.395 billion US dollars), with
falls outnumbering rises 683 to 542.  
</P>
</TEXT>
