<DOCNO> XIE19970626.0171 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bonn Strikes Deal to Sell Telecom Stake </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, June 26 (Xinhua) -- The German government said today it
will sell 25 percent of its remaining stake in the German telecom
giant Deutsche Telekom in order to meet membership targets for
joining the planned single European currency Euro.
</P>
<P>
Under a deal reached between the government and the Telekom
today, the shares are to be transferred to the state-owned Bank
for Reconstruction in 1997-98.
</P>
<P>
The move is expected to generate 25 billion German marks (14.5
billion U.S. dollars) for the financially strapped government.
</P>
<P>
The two sides also agreed that the shares would not be allowed
to be sold on the stock exchange before the year 2000, a promise
made by the government when the Telekom first went public in
November, 1996.
</P>
<P>
However, the Telekom would be permitted to offer part of the
shares to "strategic investors" in the telecommunications industry.
</P>
<P>
Telekom Chairman Ron Sommer told a general meeting of
shareholders today that the deal would help the company develop as
"a global player on the world market" by increasing its
flexibility.
</P>
<P>
Bonn currently holds about 74 percent of the Telekom
shares. 
</P>
</TEXT>
