<DOCNO> XIE19970626.0173 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Residential Mortgage Market Absorbs More Funds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Substantial amounts of new
finance continued to be channeled into the residential mortgage
market in May, according to the results of the latest survey
conducted by the Hong Kong Monetary Authority (HKMA).
</P>
<P>
Gross new loans increased during the month by 14.7 percent to
26 billion HK dollars (3.35 billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The average size of new loans increased to 1.91 million HK
dollars (246,000 U.S. dollars) compared with 1.77 million HK
dollars (228,000 U.S. dollars) in April.
</P>
<P>
Repayment of loans during May rose at a slower pace than new
loans. The amount of outstanding loans thus increased by 2.7
percent to 371.8 billion HK dollars (47.97 billion U.S. dollars)
in May, compared with a 2.4 percent increase in April.
</P>
<P>
The annualized rate of growth of outstanding loans in the three
months to May increased to 30 percent from 29.4 percent in the
three months to April. The average change over the last 12 months
increased to 24.9 percent in May from 23.1 percent in April.
</P>
<P>
David Carse, deputy Chief Executive of the HKMA, said that the
rapid growth in residential mortgage lending in May gives some
cause for concern.
</P>
<P>
However, he noted, the property market has recently been more
subdued and the HKMA is therefore continuing to evaluate the
situation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
