<DOCNO> XIE19970626.0174 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Firm to Spend More in Chilean Copper Mine </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Australian mining giant BHP Co
Ltd said it would spend 161 million US dollars as its share of a
further expansion of the Escondida development in Chile, following
approval from its partners in the copper mine.
</P>
<P>
The mine's partners agreed to a 141 million US dollar project
to optimize and integrate the original processing facility,
completed in 1990, with the subsequent three stages of expansion
completed between 1990 and mid-1996, the Australian Associated
Press reported today.
</P>
<P>
The other part of the spending would be a 140 million US dollar
investment in water supply infrastructure, which was also
approved.
</P>
<P>
The latest expansion approval would take BHP's investment in
the mine to approximately 1.5 billion US dollars.
</P>
<P>
BHP Copper's Murray Hohnen said the investment was part of a
strategy to maintain copper production levels from Escondida, as
the new expansion would allow lower grade ore through the mill
without a reduction in copper production.
</P>
<P>
It was a natural attribute of the mine that ore grades would
gradually decline.
</P>
<P>
When completed by the end of 1998, the milling capacity of the
concentrator was expected to be 127,000 tons per day, compared to
a current rate of approximately 105,000 tons per day.
</P>
<P>
The expansion would include more processing equipment such as a
24 by 34 feet ball mill, pebble crushing systems and replacement
concentrate filters at the Coloso port.
</P>
<P>
The Escondida mine yielded 845,000 tons of copper in
concentrate and copper cathode each year.
</P>
<P>
The expansion was approved by the owners of Minera Escondida
Limitada-BHP (57.5 percent), Rio Tinto plc (30 percent), Japanese
consortium JECO (10 percent) and the International Finance
Corporation (2.5 percent).  
</P>
</TEXT>
