<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South China's Haikou Lowers Land Price </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAIKOU, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Haikou, the capital city of south
China's Hainan Province, has lowered land transfer prices to
attract more overseas investment, according to an official
decision.
</P>
<P>
The decision was made in response to fund shortages arising
from dampening enthusiasm for land development by Chinese and
overseas investors after the adoption of macro economic-control
policies in 1994.
</P>
<P>
After the latest readjustment, the transfer price of per mu
land (15 mu equals one ha) will be between 25,000 and 40,000 yuan
(about 3,000-4,800 US dollars).
</P>
<P>
Land used for development of public facilities will be
transferred at 60 percent of the unit price, the decision said.
</P>
<P>
The prices cover compensations for the land, re-deployment and
the loss of young crops, according to the decision.
</P>
<P>
The original land pricing standards in Haikou were formulated
in 1992.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
