<DOCNO> XIE19970626.0187 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt to Regain Lost Antiquities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian antiquities stolen by a
British antiquities restorer will be sent back to Egypt, the
latest issue of the Egyptian Al Ahram weekly reported.
</P>
<P>
The artifacts, stolen from the Saqqara necropolis and an
ancient tomb 10 kilometers south of Giza, include a false door of
the tomb, a bronze statue of the falcon god Horus and a statue of
the head of King Amenhotep.
</P>
<P>
Last week, a British court found Jonathan Tokeley-Parry, the
smuggler, guilty of smuggling Egyptian antiquities and sentenced
him to six years in prison.
</P>
<P>
However, Tokeley-Parry justified his crime by arguing that
Egypt did not deserve to keep its own heritage because it had
neither the expertise nor the money to preserve it all.
</P>
<P>
He insisted that these treasures would be better preserved in
air-conditioned showcases in private homes than in cash-strapped
museums and stores in developing countries.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted Mohamed Saleh, director of the Egyptian
Museum, as saying that there is an unwritten "regulation of
cooperation" between the world's museums, under which a stolen
object which a trader tries to sell to a museum should be returned
to the country of origin.
</P>
<P>
Egyptologists have often demanded a change in British law which
does not penalize anyone who steals artifacts from a foreign
country, as long as the crime was committed outside the UK.
</P>
<P>
Last February, a Cairo court sentenced Tokeley-Parry in
absentia to 15 years hard labor for being part of a 12-man
smuggling ring that include corrupt Egyptian antiquities
inspectors. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970626.0188 </DOCNO>
