<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK New Airport to Go into Operation Next April </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Construction of Hong Kong's new
international airport at Chek Lap Kok has been going on smoothly
and the airport will go into service next April as planned,
according to Clinton Leeks, director of corporate development of
the Airport Authority.
</P>
<P>
At a press briefing in the Hong Kong Convention and Exhibition
Center today, Clinton Leeks said the south runway of the new
airport will be put into use in April, 1998, while the north
runway, whose construction started last April, will be ready for
use the following November.
</P>
<P>
The new airport on Lantau island east of Hong Kong Island will
be able to handle 35 million passengers and three million tonnes
of cargo a year, Leeks said.
</P>
<P>
The new airport's annual passenger and cargo flow is expected
to reach 87 million persons and nine million tonnes by the year
2004.
</P>
<P>
Rail and highway links, bridges, a cross-sea tunnel and new
town facilities to support the airport are also under
construction, said Leeks, and it will take only 23 minutes to
travel from Central, Hong Kong's business center, to the new
airport by a high-speed train.
</P>
<P>
With shuttle trains and escalators installed in the airport,
according to Leeks, passengers only need 30 minutes to go through
all check-in and check-out procedures.
</P>
<P>
The director said the Airport Authorities are discussing with
airlines and other bodies involved on airport charges which he
revealed will be at a "medium level."
</P>
<P>
Leeks said the name of the new airport will be decided by the
government of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region.
</P>
<P>
When the new airport opens to service, he said, the present Kai
Tak Airport will be closed.  
</P>
</TEXT>
