<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijing To Move "Closer" to Sea </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 26 (Xinhua) -- As of next year, Beijingers won't
have to dream about voyages in the South China Sea to see
dolphins, man-eating sharks, coral and colorful shells, after the
announcement from Beijing Zoo that a huge aquarium is to be built
there.
</P>
<P>
The Beijing Aquarium, expected to cover 35,000 square meters
will not only be China's first marine world, but also the largest
in any of Asia's land-locked cities.
</P>
<P>
The conch-shaped aquarium will provide an underwater home away
from the sea to sharks, whales and another 1,500 marine
creatures. But to ensure more than just the survival of the
fittest, the fish will be divided among one huge "ocean" pool,
containing 2,000 tons of sea water, and 30 smaller "seas", each
holding about 20 tons of water.
</P>
<P>
Visitors will be able to watch marine life through large, solid
acrylic panes which provide 99 percent transparency. And they may
also feel just how prickly sea urchins and sea stars are which
will be easy to pick up from a long, open water tank. Meanwhile,
the eccentrics of the sea, dolphins and sea lions, will show off
their playful skills before an audience seated in a 3,000-seat
marina-arena.
</P>
<P>
The aquarium will not only break records for the diversity of
its future tenants -- it is going to shatter glazing records: it
will feature a great "glass" wall measuring ten by six meters and
weighing 23 tons.
</P>
<P>
According to a manager with Beijing Landa Aquarium
Co. Ltd. which is investing US$56 million in the project, the
pane, which is acrylic not glass, is the second biggest in the
world, after one in a San Francisco aquarium.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970626.0196 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Job Growth's Hopes Given Boost in Australia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Hopes of an improved outlook for
employment growth in Australia were given a boost today with an
increase in the number of job vacancies.
</P>
<P>
An Australian Bureau of Statistics (ABS) survey found the total
job vacancies rose 2.7 percent, seasonally adjusted, to 63,900 in
the May quarter compared with the previous three months.
</P>
<P>
The survey, released here today, found the job vacancies were
now 7.7 percent higher than in the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
The quarterly increase was solely due to a greater demand for
labor in the private sector, with the public sector job vacancies
falling 12.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
Economists believed signs of improvement in today's ABS job
vacancies would be a good guide to the size of an expected pick-up
in the job growth.
</P>
<P>
Last month employment fell by 40,300 in the country, while the
unemployment rate rose to a three-month high of 8.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
Federal Treasurer Peter Costello told parliament this morning
that a near record number of job vacancies in the May quarter
supported the outlook for stronger employment growth in the coming
months.
</P>
<P>
He promised that the government would continue to take measures
to reduce the Commonwealth debt, return the budget to surplus and
improve industrial relations.
</P>
<P>
He believed these will create sustainable real jobs in the
private sector and reduce the high unemployment rate in the months
to come. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
