<HEADLINE> Bolivia Downs Mexico for Copa America Final </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LA PAZ, June 25 (Xinhua) -- Bolivia defeated Mexico 3-1
Wednesday night to qualify for the Copa America final, raising the
hopes to clinch the title for the first time since 1963.
</P>
<P>
The other berth will be contested between Brazil and Peru to be
played in Santa Cruz.
</P>
<P>
After the victory, soccer fans hit the streets in celebration
as Bolivia kept its slate intact in the Latin America's most
important soccer championship.
</P>
<P>
The game was suspended for nine minutes after the Mexicans
questioned the referee for ruling on one of the goals. And both
coaches, Antonio Lopez of Bolivia and Bora Milutinovic of Mexico,
were thus expelled.
</P>
<P>
Mexico's Nicolas Ramirez scored at fourth minute with a free
kick, but the Bolivians turned the match around with goals by
Erwin Sanchez, Ramiro Castillo and Jaime Moreno at 26, 44 and 75
minutes.
</P>
<P>
Two Mexican players of Claudio Suarez and Joel Sanchez were
expelled from the game at 44 and 76 minutes. 
</P>
