<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Muslim Rebels Take 100 Passengers As Hostage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Some 150 heavily armed Muslim
rebels today flagged down two passenger buses along a highway in
the southern Philippines, taking some 100 people on board as
hostages, military reports said.
</P>
<P>
Reports said the Moro Islamic Liberation Front (MILF) rebels
herded at gunpoints the passengers in the village of Malabuwaya,
Kabacan, North Cotabato province in Mindanao.
</P>
<P>
General Arnulfo Acedera, chief-of-staff of the armed forces,
said the hostage taking was the MILF's diversionary tactic to ease
the government's full blown attacks on Rajamuda in North Cotabato,
the MILF's second biggest camp in Mindanao.
</P>
<P>
"We will exert all efforts to keep the hostages free and safe,"
Acedera said.
</P>
<P>
He said government troops surrounded the rebels in the rugged
hills of Kabacan where intense fighting resulted in undetermined
number of casualties.
</P>
<P>
Sketchy military reports said the rebels had released 40 people
and left only 60 captives while other unconfirmed reports said
many of the hostages tried to escape during the ensuing battle,
forcing the rebels to shoot and kill two of them.
</P>
<P>
Government troops intensified military operations against the
MILF after some rebels took 43 employees of the Philippine Oil Co.
on June 16. All hostages had been rescued by the military.
</P>
<P>
However, the two sides continued their fighting since then.
Earlier reports said that some 100 rebels and five soldiers had
been killed during the ongoing battles.
</P>
<P>
The MILF had threatened to quit peace talks with the government
if the military continues its operations.  
