<HEADLINE> More Financial Institutions Move to Shanghai's Bund </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, June 26 (Xinhua) -- The Bund of Shanghai, China's
economic center, is regaining its status as a financial center in
the Far East as more financial institutions move to the area.
</P>
<P>
Official sources said that a total of 15 Chinese and overseas
financial institutions and some multinationals have moved to
office buildings on the Bund, and more are expected to follow.
</P>
<P>
The financial institutions and companies include the Shanghai
Pudong Development Bank, the Bangkok Bank of Thailand, the
Citibank of the United States, the ABN-AMRO Bank of the
Netherlands, the American Insurance Company, the China Foreign
Exchange Trade System, the Citibank of United States, the
Everbright Bank of China, the Huaxia Bank, the AJ Trust &AMP;
Investment Corp., and Kong Kong's Park View Company.
</P>
<P>
To rebuild the Bund into a financial center, the Shanghai
Municipal Government in 1995 launched an effort to switch the
owners and users of the office buildings on the Bund from
government agencies to financial institutions, regional
headquarters of consortia and service companies.
</P>
<P>
There are altogether 240 buildings in the Bund area. 
</P>
