<HEADLINE> Standard Chartered Bank Optimistic with HK's Future </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 26 (Xinhua) -- The future of Hong Kong as a
business and financial center is bright, according to a report
issued by Standard Chartered Bank recently.
</P>
<P>
K.C. Kwok, chief economist for HK, China and Northeast Asia of
Standard Chartered, was quoted as saying that Hong Kong has gone
from strength to strength during the past 15 years,
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong's stock of outward foreign direct investment is
estimated to be the equivalent of 63 percent of its GDP, which is
much higher than the 28 percent for Britain, 16 percent for
Singapore, 10 percent for Taiwan, nine percent for the United
States and six percent for Japan.
</P>
<P>
This indicated that a large number of companies are managing
their investments in China and in the region, with their bases in
Hong Kong, the report said.
</P>
<P>
It went on to note that Hong Kong's economic performance is
strong, and is set to remain so after its return to China,
underpinned by robust consumption and investment, adding that many
business service sectors are doing well and prospects for trade
look encouraging.
</P>
<P>
The growth has been promoted by not only the enormous business
opportunities unleashed by the reforms and development in China's
interior area, but also by the flexibility and entrepreneurial
dynamism of the Hong Kong economy.
</P>
<P>
With regard to China's development, the report said, many media
reports and comments on China tend to focus on the negative
aspects.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the reported noted, since China remains a low-income
developing country with its own historical, cultural and social
peculiarities, one should not be blind to the fact that hundreds
of millions of people in China today are enjoying a level of
material living standard and spiritual freedom unprecedented in
Chinese history. 
</P>
</TEXT>
