<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indian Central Bank Cuts Bank Rate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, June 26 (Xinhua) -- In a significant development,
the Reserve Bank of India (RBI) on Wednesday slashed the bank rate
by one percentage point from 11 to 10 percent with immediate
effect, the Times of India reported today.
</P>
<P>
The bank rate is the rate at which the RBI makes money
available to the banking system in the country and any
fluctuations in this rate should reflect in the interest movements
in the economy.
</P>
<P>
The RBI decision to cut the bank rate has sent out a signal
that the central bank wants a lower interest rate regime and is
trying to nudge the banking system, now flush with funds, to lend
more freely to business and industry.
</P>
<P>
The move is the first evidence of the central bank living up to
its earlier promise of using this rate as a benchmark for monetary
management.
</P>
<P>
The immediate outcome of the cut in the bank rate would be a
fall in the interest ceiling on domestic term deposits of maturity
between 30 days and one year from 9 to 8 percent.
</P>
<P>
Thus, the cost of funds to banks will be lower by 1 percentage
point while these banks will be expected to pass on this benefit
to their borrowers by lowering their lending rates.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, the central bank's decision will have an overall
impact of lowering various interest rates in the market, making
more funds available for Indian business and industry.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970626.0219 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-26 </DATE_TIME>
