<HEADLINE> NZ Budget Lays Stress on Health, Education </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, June 26 (Xinhua) -- New Zealand Treasurer Winston
Peters delivered his first budget for the country over the next
three years this afternoon, putting emphasis on health and
education.
</P>
<P>
In line with an agreement the National Party and the New
Zealand First party signed last December to form the first
coalition government in the country, health, education and some
other sectors are the major gainers in the budget.
</P>
<P>
"The budget recognizes the importance of social
responsibilities and shows our commitment to delivering on the
Coalition Agreement promises in health, education, employment,
safer communities, the environment, saving for retirement and to
older New Zealanders," Peters stated.
</P>
<P>
The key budget initiatives and the three-year cost of these
initiatives include improving the health and well-being of New
Zealanders at an additional cost of 900 million NZ dollars (one NZ
dollar equals 0.68 U.S. dollars), raising the quality of education
through increased funding of 355 million dollars and removing the
superannuation surcharge at a cost of 554 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
The coalition agreement envisages that an extra 5 billion
dollars are needed in the next three years to be spent on priority
areas, most in health, education and social welfare.
</P>
<P>
Peters said the government's intention is to stay within the 5
billion dollar limit set out in the agreement.
</P>
<P>
He said that in 1997/98, new spending will total 900 million
dollars, rising to 1.6 billion dollars in 1998/99 and 2.5 billion
dollars in 1999/2000.
</P>
<P>
He predicted that after taking into account new spending
initiatives, and tax cuts in 1998/99, which were announced by the
former government but put off for one year by the coalition, the
government operating surpluses are forecast to rise from 1.5
percent of the GDP in 1997/98 to 2.3 percent in 1999/2000. Over
the same period, net government debt is forecast to fall from 25.5
percent, he added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
