<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> hkhk - Hong Kong-related Data (12): Major Institutions of HKSAR </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 26 (Xinhua) -- With regard to the establishment
of institutions in the future Hong Kong Special Administrative
Region (HKSAR), the Basic Law follows the spirit of the
Sino-British Joint Declaration and takes into consideration the
characteristics of the political system of the HKSAR.
</P>
<P>
In accordance with the spirit of the Joint Declaration, no
changes will be made unless such changes are necessary, and no
changes will be made if such changes are undesirable.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, good elements in the existing institutions will be
either assimilated or retained.
</P>
<P>
Given the characteristics of the political system of the HKSAR,
there will be neither a complete copying of the names of existing
institutions, nor a duplication of the people's congress,
procuratorate and judicial systems, nor a patterning after the
administrative structure in China's inland areas.
</P>
<P>
The most important institutions of the HKSAR are the Chief
Executive, the Government, the Legislative Council and the Court
of Final Appeal.
</P>
<P>
In addition, there are the Executive Council as well as the
Commission Against Corruption and the Commission of Audit, both of
which will work independently and are accountable to the Chief
Executive.
</P>
<P>
Under the HKSAR Government will be a department of
administration, a department of finance, a department of justice
and various bureaus, divisions and commissions.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970626.0223 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> hkhk - Hong Kong-related Data (13): Powers and Functions of Chief </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 26 (Xinhua) -- As the Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region (HKSAR) enjoys a high degree of autonomy,
its Chief Executive has fairly extensive powers and functions.
They are as follows:
</P>
<P>
1. To lead the government of the HKSAR;
</P>
<P>
2. To be responsible for the implementation of the Basic law
and other laws which, in accordance with the Basic Law, apply in
the HKSAR;
</P>
<P>
3. To sign bills passed by the Legislative Council and to
promulgate laws; to sign budgets passed by the Legislative Council
and report the budgets and final accounts to the Central People's
Government for the record;
</P>
<P>
4. To decide on government policies and to issue executive
orders;
</P>
<P>
5. To nominate, and report to the Central People's Government
for appointment, the following principal officials: Secretaries
and Deputy Secretaries of Departments, Directors of Bureaus,
Commissioner Against Corruption, Director of Audit, Commissioner
of Police, Director of Immigration and Commissioner of Customs and
Excise; and to recommend to the Central People's Government the
removal of the above-mentioned officials;
</P>
<P>
6. To appoint or remove judges of the courts at all levels in
accordance with legal procedures;
</P>
<P>
7. To appoint or remove holders of public office in accordance
with legal procedures;
</P>
<P>
8. To implement the directives issued by the Central People's
Government in respect of the relevant matters provided for in the
Basic Law;
</P>
<P>
9. To conduct, on behalf of the government of the HKSAR,
external affairs and other affairs as authorized by the Central
People's Government;
</P>
<P>
10. To approve the introduction of motions regarding revenues
or expenditures to the Legislative Council;
</P>
<P>
11. To decide, in the light of security and vital public
interests, whether government officials or other personnel in
charge of government affairs should testify or give evidence
before the Legislative Council or its committees;
</P>
<P>
12. To pardon persons convicted of criminal offenses or commute
their penalties; and
</P>
<P>
13. To handle petitions and complaints.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
