<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NZ Not to Privatize Six Strategic Assets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, June 26 (Xinhua) -- The New Zealand coalition
government reconfirmed today its commitment to retaining the six
strategic assets listed in an agreement on forming the coalition.
</P>
<P>
In a joint speech in the parliament, Finance Minister Bill
Birch and State Owned Enterprises (SOE) Minister Jenny Shipley
said the coalition agreement is the first time in the 10-year
history of SOEs that the government has made a clear statement
that a specified group of assets will not be privatized.
</P>
<P>
The two ministers, who are the SOEs' government shareholders,
said however that the government will take steps to ensure the six
SOEs listed in the agreement will be managed as efficiently as
possible.
</P>
<P>
"This includes ensuring that each SOE has a fully commercial
capital structure and does not retain funds that could be better
used elsewhere."
</P>
<P>
The government will ask each SOE Board to ensure that its SOE
has an appropriate capital structure, including a debt-to-equity
ratio at least as high as that of comparable private sector
entities.
</P>
<P>
The six SOEs listed as strategic assets are the NZ Energy
Corporation, the Contact Energy company, the Trans Power company,
New Zealand Post, TV One and Radio New Zealand.  
</P>
</TEXT>
