<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wheat Output Expected to Touch Record in India </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, June 26 (Xinhua) -- The production of foodgrains in
India is estimated to reach 198.17 million tons this year (from
July 1996 to June 1997) with indications that the wheat output
will be the highest ever at 68.71 million tons, the Times of India
reported today.
</P>
<P>
The Indian Agriculture Ministry, which released the statistics
on Wednesday, had in April estimated that foodgrains production
would be 192.12 million tons.
</P>
<P>
But the ministry has revised the estimate upward following
indications that the wheat output, earlier forecast to be 64.66
million tons, might touch 68.71 million tons on the basis of the
latest production data sent in by the states in which wheat is
grown.
</P>
<P>
The previous highest wheat production of 65.77 million tons was
achieved in 1994-95.
</P>
<P>
India has suffered from a shortage in wheat supplies since last
year and imported millions of tons of wheat from other countries
to meet the demand of domestic market.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a press conference here on Wednesday, Indian
Agriculture Minister Chaturanan Mishra said there would be no need
to import wheat this year to help sustain the public distribution
system in the country.
</P>
<P>
But he warned that the government would not hesitate to import
foodgrains if the trade manipulated the market prices of wheat
beyond reasonable levels.
</P>
<P>
He also said that the government had taken note of warnings of
a few international scientists that warming of Pacific ocean
waters due to the El Nino phenomenon could adversely affect
monsoon rainfall in India. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
