<DOCNO> XIE19970626.0227 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Myanmar Seizes 5,534 Kilos of Narcotic Drugs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Myanmar authorities destroyed 24
heroin refineries and seized a total of 5,534.54 kilograms of
narcotic drugs in the country in 1996 and up to the first quarter
of 1997, a senior drug control official said today.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a ceremony here marking the International Day
Against Drug Abuse and Illicit Trafficking, Mya Thin, chairman of
the Central Committee for Drug Abuse Control (CCDAC), said the
seizure included 936.1 kilograms of heroin and 4554.3 kilograms of
opium.
</P>
<P>
Altogether 5,030 offenses and 7,345 offenders are under trial,
said Mya Thin, who is also the minister for home affairs.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the Mongla area in Eastern Shan State has been
proclaimed as an opium free zone in March this year, adding that
more similar zones will be set up in the Wa area in northern Shan
State under a three-year project and emphasis have been put on
ending the cultivation of opium poppy and marijuana in Kachin
special regions since 1991.
</P>
<P>
He also said Myanmar plans to take part in a meeting among
Myanmar, Thailand and Laos in Laos and another six-nation meeting
in Thailand concerning drug control.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar is also cooperating with neighboring countries like
Thailand, Laos, China, India and Bangladesh and with the Russian
Federation and Vietnam, having signed bilateral agreements with
them, he added.
</P>
<P>
With a view to joining the common fight against narcotic drugs
in the region, Myanmar handed over to the Thai authorities
captured Li Yan Chin, alias Pongsat Rojanasat Sakul, an absconder
charged with drug trafficking at a criminal court of Thailand, he
further noted.  
</P>
</TEXT>
