<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Becomes International CEC Center </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Some 13,000 financiers and
numerous heads of state will come to Hong Kong in September to
attend the annual meeting of the World Bank and the International
Monetary Fund.
</P>
<P>
This will be the first international conference Hong Kong is to
host after it returns to China and one of 60 large international
conferences to be held in Hong Kong in the next eight years.
</P>
<P>
Informed sources say more than 170 international conferences
and 400 exhibitions will be held in Hong Kong before the year
2005. This year will see the convening of close to 90
international conferences and exhibitions, averaging three a day.
</P>
<P>
They deal with a wide range of subjects covering architecture,
machinery, commerce, finance, transport, telecommunications, law,
science, culture, education, garment and jewelry.
</P>
<P>
An official of the Hong Kong Tourist Association said that Hong
Kong has become an international conference and exhibition center,
which is compatible with its status as an international financial,
trade and tourist center. It will contribute greatly to China's
economic development.
</P>
<P>
Serving as a prime venue for international conferences and
exhibitions is bound to speed up the development of tourism in
Hong Kong, he said, estimating the number of visitors for each
conference or exhibition at 2,000.
</P>
<P>
The majority of these international conferences and exhibitions
will be held at the Hong Kong Convention and Exhibition Center,
which is to become the second largest of its kind in Asia when the
center's 4.8-billion HK dollar extension starts operation on July
1.
</P>
<P>
With five exhibition halls, two convention halls, two speaking
halls and 52 meeting rooms, the center can accommodate 140,000
visitors a day. 
</P>
</TEXT>
