<HEADLINE> Aid Group to Support Nepal in Poverty Alleviation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, June 26 (Xinhua) -- The Nepal Aid Group has pledged
to support the Nepali government in its policies and programs
related to macroeconomic management and poverty alleviation.
</P>
<P>
Representatives from the aid group, including Japan, the United
States, Germany, the World Bank and the International Monetary
Fund, said here Wednesday that they appreciate the economic reform
measures of the present Nepali government and they are in broad
agreement with the policies it has adopted.
</P>
<P>
They also stressed the importance of fiscal balance,
mobilization of internal resources and privatization, the local
press reported today.
</P>
<P>
Nepali Finance Minister Rabindra Nath Sharma said the
government will pursue liberal economic policies and promote and
strengthen the economic reform process initiated a few years ago.
</P>
<P>
And the Nepali government is committed to achieving a high
economic growth and reduce poverty in the country, Sharma said
when meeting the local representatives of the Nepal Aid Group at a
time when the fiscal year of 1997-98 will begin on July 15.
</P>
<P>
Noting the low productivity of agriculture in the country,
Sharma said the Agriculture Perspective Plan, expected to be
implemented from fiscal year 1998-99, will significantly
contribute to raising agricultural productivity and reducing
poverty.
</P>
<P>
He added that the government is also committed to the
privatization program and reforms will be introduced in several
areas including trade, industry, foreign investment, banking,
finance and pricing policy.
</P>
<P>
The government intends to introduce various reform measures in
tax administration, including the introduction of value added tax
in the coming fiscal year, Sharma said.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that Nepal's overall economic indicators have not
been discouraging so far and external assistance has been playing
an important role in the country's economic development.  
</P>
</TEXT>
