<HEADLINE> Frog Farming Introduced into Nicaragua </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANAGUA, June 25 (Xinhua) -- Breeding frogs could become a new
business option soon in Nicaragua, says a Salvadoran expert.
</P>
<P>
Jose Trinidad Benitez made the prediction at the first seminar
in the country on raising frogs, which opened here Tuesday and was
sponsored by the Agriculture and Livestock Ministry and the
International Regional Organization of Plant and Animal Health.
</P>
<P>
Benitez said the main reason for raising frogs was for export
for hard currencies.
</P>
<P>
At present, the market price of frog legs for export is seven
U.S. dollars a pound.
</P>
<P>
In his country, Benitez said, companies had been able to ship
up to 1000 pounds a month of the profitable legs to the United
States, where they were appreciated as a delicious food, tastier
and with more protein than fish and chicken.
</P>
<P>
In El Salvador and Guatemala, which are experienced in breeding
batrachia, frog legs are on the menus of four and five star
restaurants. Many Europeans and Asians also eat frog legs.
</P>
</TEXT>
