<HEADLINE> Three Suspected Child Lifters Lynched in Dhaka </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, June 26 (Xinhua) -- A group of agitated people on
Wednesday torched a police van, roasting two suspected child
lifters in it and beat another to death at the North Badda area in
Bangladesh's capital city, Dhaka, the local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
It is the second time in a month that suspected kidnappers and
thieves were lynched around Dhaka by mass beating. Just a month
ago, six cattle thieves were beaten to death in Demra County,
dozens of kilometers southeast of Dhaka.
</P>
<P>
During the violent clashes on Wednesday, another person was
shot dead and 18 policemen were injured when police tried to
rescue the three suspected child lifters from the wrath of the
mob.
</P>
<P>
The mob torched the van when police snatched the three severely
beaten alleged child lifters from the mob and took them on to the
van. However, one of the victims was dragged out of the van and
beaten to death.
</P>
<P>
Police said they fired 31 shots and 34 tear gas shells to bring
the riotous mob under control and arrested 25 people from the spot
during and after the incident.
</P>
<P>
Home Minister Rafiqul Islam later told the parliament that some
people might have provoked the lynching. He sought cooperation
from all political parties in maintaining law and order.
Otherwise, he said, innocent people might fall victim.
</P>
<P>
The minister also urged people not to take the law into their
own hands, but hand over suspects to police.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the opposition Bangladesh Nationalist Party (BNP)
accused the government and its law-enforcing agencies of failing
to remove the panic created among the people across the country
over the child-lifting incident.
</P>
<P>
"The incident proves that the people have lost their confidence
in the law-enforcing agencies," BNP Secretary General Abdul Mannan
said in a statement.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
