<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Funds Pour into Shenzhen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENZHEN, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong investment in the
Futian bonded zone of Shenzhen, a special economic zone in south
China, has grown rapidly since the start of this year, official
figures show.
</P>
<P>
Thirty-four Hong Kong-funded enterprises were registered in
Futian between January and May, with registered capital totaling
312 million Hong Kong dollars, up 160 percent over the same period
of last year.
</P>
<P>
Funds from Hong Kong have accounted for nearly 70 percent of
all overseas investment in the bonded zone, which added up to 2.4
billion Hong Kong dollars by the end of last month.
</P>
<P>
As overseas capital rushes in, imports and exports in the
bonded zone have surged, reaching 541 million US dollars last
year, or more than double the 1995 figure.
</P>
<P>
A zone official said that the growth momentum is able to be
sustained this year, with exports and imports expected to reach
1.78 billion US dollars.
</P>
<P>
The bonded zone, designed to become a comprehensive free trade
zone, will play an important role in economic development in
Shenzhen, a city official noted.
</P>
<P>
He predicted that the zone's gross domestic product would reach
10 billion yuan (about 1.2 billion US dollars) by the year 2000
while imports and exports would hit six billion US dollars.
</P>
</TEXT>
