<HEADLINE> Shanghai Bank Transfers Foreign Exchange Business to Subsidiaries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, June 26 (Xinhua) -- The Shanghai branch of the
Industrial and Commercial Bank of China (ICBC), the country's
largest bank, will transfer its credit business in foreign
exchange to its grassroots subsidiaries as of July 1, according to
a bank decision.
</P>
<P>
The bank's international business department, which until now
has been in charge of the foreign exchange credit business, will
mainly be responsible for the administration of foreign exchange
loans beginning next month.
</P>
<P>
Analysts say that the decision to transfer the foreign exchange
credit business down to the grassroots subsidiaries is an
important step taken by ICBC Shanghai to meet the need of banking
commercialization.
</P>
<P>
The latest measure will be helpful in preventing risks related
to the extension of loans in foreign exchange, the analysts noted.
</P>
<P>
Covered by the decision are loans for technical renovation,
marginal loans for overseas-funded enterprises, packing loans,
loans for circulating funds, and loans already agreed to but not
extended.
</P>
<P>
The value of loans falling within the perimeters of the
decision accounts for 75 percent of all loans from the bank's
international business department, according to bank estimates.
</P>
</TEXT>
