<HEADLINE> OPEC Decides to Maintain Oil Production Ceiling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
VIENNA, June 25 (Xinhua) -- The Organization of Petroleum
Exporting Countries (OPEC) nations agreed today to maintain the
current official production ceiling of 25.03 million barrels daily.
</P>
<P>
Secretary-General of OPEC, Rilwanu Lukman, told reporters that
the ministerial meeting of OPEC decided that all 11 member
countries would keep the group's production quotas in the second
half of this year, with no changes in quotas of member countries.
</P>
<P>
Local observers estimated that OPEC production now stands at
two million barrels a day above its ceiling of 25.03 million
barrels.
</P>
<P>
Since early this year, the oil average price has dropped from
25 U.S. dollars a barrel to the present level of about 18 dollars
a barrel, well below the group's target of 21 dollars.
</P>
<P>
The meeting opened here today and will end on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The Austrian News Agency APA said that most of the member
countries agreed to maintain the group's current official ceiling,
while Saudi Arabia and Iran hoped OPEC member countries would
abide by their allotment. However, Venezuela, reportedly the
biggest overproducer, demanded an extension, even lift the ceiling.
</P>
<P>
Iraqi Oil Minister Amer Rasheed said his country would get back
into the export market within 10 days in accordance with the
United Nations conditions.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has been banned from most oil exporting since it invaded
Kuwait, another OPEC member country, in 1991. The UN has now
agreed to allow Iraq to sell limited amounts of oil to buy food
and drugs for its people.
</P>
<P>
Secretary-General Lukman said Iraq's return to the market could
not influence oil prices.
</P>
<P>
The organization's members are Algeria, Indonesia, Iran, Iraq,
Kuwait, Libya, Nigeria, Qatar, Saudi Arabia, United Arab Emirates
and Venezuela. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
