<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Authorizes Colombian Fish Imports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTAFE DE BOGOTA, June 25 (Xinhua) -- The European Union (EU)
authorized the imports of Colombian fish which it believes
meets its sanitary and quality standards.
</P>
<P>
The certification was extended after a recent inspection made in
this South American country by Isabel Sanz, an EU expert in fish
sanitation inspection, said the authorities cited today by
Colprensa, Colombia's news agency.
</P>
<P>
The EU expert visited processing plants located in
Cartagena, Barranquilla, Tumaco, Buenaventura and other regions
in Colombia.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, Colombian fish exports reached 200 million U.S. dollars,
of which 97 million or 49 percent corresponded to the European
Union.
</P>
<P>
Colombia's main sea product exports in 1996 were tuna fish (88
million dollars) and shrimp (104 million dollars).
</P>
<P>
Since January 1996, Colombia has received a preferential tariff
of 24 percent on its tuna fish and 4 percent on its shrimp exports
vis-a-vis other international suppliers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
