<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong's Water Supply - A Long Story </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Guess what answer you might get
when you ask a group of Hong Kong kids where fresh water comes
from.
</P>
<P>
"Rainfall," one says. "From the reservoir I visited last
summer," another cuts in. But you shouldn't feel amused if a third
offers: "Simply from the tap!"
</P>
<P>
After all, they are kids, too little to know what a long way
fresh water has come into their life.
</P>
<P>
The older generations, however, will never forget the story of
water, which makes an important part of Hong Kong's history.
</P>
<P>
For most of the past 150-odd years, the city suffered severe
water shortages due to the lack of natural resources -- lakes,
rivers or substantial underground water.
</P>
<P>
Healthy but erratic rainfall, which averages 2,214 millimeters
a year, had been the major source of water supply till the early
1960s.
</P>
<P>
In the century up to the 1960s, one Hong Kong governor after
another seemed to share the same perspective that rain water alone
would be able to meet the needs of the people as long as enough
reservoirs were built.
</P>
<P>
In 1860 when Governor Hercules Robinson was in office, work on
Hong Kong's first public water scheme -- Pok Fu Lam Reservoir --
was started. Its supplies began to reach the city at the end of
1863, and that was the year Hong Kong first had its tap water.
</P>
<P>
But, upon completion, the scheme, with a capacity of only 9,000
cubic meters, proved hopelessly inadequate for the then nearly
100,000 population.
</P>
<P>
As a result, many bigger reservoirs were constructed in the
following years throughout Hong Kong, such as Tai Tam Tuk
Reservoir, Aberdeen Lower Reservoir, Shing Mun Reservoir and Shek
Pik Reservoir.
</P>
<P>
Unfortunately, none of them managed to catch up with the rising
population and the ever-increasing demand for water, particularly
in case of drought.
</P>
<P>
"Up to late 1967, restricted water supply was the rule rather
than the exception," said a government fact sheet.
</P>
<P>
In 1895 when a drought hit Hong Kong, there was only daytime
water supply.
</P>
<P>
In 1902 the supply was cut to one hour a day and water was
brought from the Pearl River by boat.
</P>
<P>
When a severe drought visited the city in 1929, compartments of
trains running between Kowloon and Guangdong were transformed into
tanks to bring water from Shenzhen River.
</P>
<P>
Then came the year 1963, a nightmare to most of middle-aged
Hong Kongers. Supply was restricted to four hours every four days.
</P>
<P>
Many factories were forced to shut down, leaving tens of
thousands of people jobless overnight.
</P>
<P>
The 3 million people were plunged into dire straits. A
photographer recorded the pitiful scene: an endless queue of empty
buckets on the street awaiting a refill with anxious women
standing nearby.
</P>
<P>
A large fleet of chartered tankers transported water from the
Pearl River to feed the thirsty city.
</P>
<P>
It was the 1963 drought that led to the construction of the
well-known Dongjiang-Shenzhen water project on the mainland, which
proved to be the best solution to Hong Kong's water problem.
</P>
<P>
The then Chinese premier, Zhou Enlai, approved the project,
allocating some 36 million yuan RMB!!(4.6 million U.S. dollars)
out of the state coffers at a time when China's economy was
experiencing a hard time.
</P>
<P>
With the project completed at the beginning of 1965 after 11
months of work, water was extracted from Dongjiang, or the East
River, at a point some 83 kilometers north of Hong Kong, pumped
over a series of dams and eventually discharged into the Shenzhen
Reservoir before being fed by pipeline across the border to Hong
Kong.
</P>
<P>
After so many years of suffering from the water shortage and
restricted supply, Hong Kong finally saw a gleam of hope.
</P>
<P>
In the 1970s, 1980s and 1990s, the water project has been
expanded three times, with its capacity growing from 68 million
cubic meters to over 700 million cubic meters.
</P>
<P>
Figures show that in 1986 water from Dongjiang made up about 52
percent of Hong Kong's demand. In 1996, the ratio was raised to
over 70 percent with the annual supply hitting 720 million cubic
meters.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong people benefit a lot from the project -- at least a
shower every day is guaranteed, while visitors and tourists have
the chance to enjoy a variety of artificial fountains and
waterfalls in parks and in front of high-rise buildings.
</P>
<P>
As Director of Water Supplies Hui Man-shiu said, water coming
from Dongjiang is the origin of Hong Kong's vitality.  
</P>
</TEXT>
