<HEADLINE> Philippines' Palace Allegedly Backs Charter Change </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 26 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine Presidential Palace
helped a pro-charter change group advocate constitutional
amendment to allow a second term for President Fidel Ramos, the
Manila Chronicle reported today.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted Mike Policarpio, executive director of the
People's Initiative for Reform, Modernization and Action (PIRMA),
as saying the palace was instrumental in helping the group hurdle
obstacles that stood in the way of its signature campaign.
</P>
<P>
"The Ramos administration has been effective in removing some
stumbling blocks we have faced and are facing because it
recognized there are these 6 million signatures and there is a
clear chance for people's initiative to push for charter changes,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, the PIRMA tried its third chance by submitting to
the Commission on Elections 6 million signatures it collected.
Earlier, the Supreme Court had twice foiled the PIRMA's efforts.
</P>
<P>
Policarpio's remarks came after Budget Secretary Salvador
Enriquez announced that President Ramos was interested in seeking
a second term but was "too shy to say it."
</P>
<P>
Enriquez also revealed that six cabinet members, including
himself, have signed in the PIRMA petition.
</P>
<P>
However, Policarpio refused to say how the palace helped PIRMA.
He also denied the palace was "using the group" to extend the term
of the president.  
</P>
</TEXT>
