<HEADLINE> Thailand, Myanmar to Jointly Develop Economic Zone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Thailand and Myanmar are likely to
join hands in developing a special economic zone in Myanmar's
Myawaddy Province, which borders Thailand's Tak Province.
</P>
<P>
The Myanmar government has confirmed its support for the
establishment of the economic zone to facilitate the relocation of
Thai labor-intensive industries to Myanmar, the Thai Prime
Minister's Office Minister Veerakorn Kamprakob said on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Thai labor-intensive industries, like garment and shoe
manufacturing, will relocate their production bases from Thailand
to the zone to utilize the cheap labor in Myanmar, he said.
</P>
<P>
Local newspapers reported that the labor cost in Myawaddy was
only 16 baht per day, much lower than the minimum daily wages of
between 128 and 157 baht (5.12-5.28 U.S. dollars) in Thailand.
</P>
<P>
Thai officials also believed that the establishment of such an
industrial estate will help solve the illegal foreign labor
problems in Thailand.
</P>
<P>
The Myanmar government hoped to bring its laborers back from
Thailand by establishing the zone, Veerakorn said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
