<HEADLINE> IOC Warns Bidding Cities Against Commercialism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 25 (Xinhua) -- Olympic chiefs have warned the five
cities bidding to host the 2004 Summer Games that the
commercialism which sparked huge controversy at last year's
Atlanta Olympics must disappear for good.
</P>
<P>
International Olympic Committee (IOC) marketing director
Michael Payne said on Wednesday the issue was a key part of a
Tuesday meeting which the IOC held with the bidding cities --
Rome, Athens, Buenos Aires, Cape Town and Stockholm.
</P>
<P>
Atlanta was heavily criticised for commercial excesses, which
had almost made the Games look like a huge flea market.
</P>
<P>
The IOC has a number of official sponsors and rules about how
the Olympic Games can be used in advertising.
</P>
<P>
Last year the organisation said it would be tightening its
rules on commercialism and would not give the Games to cities in
the future unless they agreed with its marketing plans.
</P>
<P>
Payne said Sydney, which hosts the next Summer Games in the
year 2000, had already introduced even tougher rules on
commercialism than the IOC requires. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
