<HEADLINE> NATO Workshop Closes After Intense Discussion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PRAGUE, June 25 (Xinhua) -- The 14th International Workshop on
the future of the North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO) ends
here today after intensified discussion on political and security
issues, military cooperation and alliance's eastward expansion.
</P>
<P>
The five-day seminar began last weekend. Presidents, prime
ministers and foreign and defense ministers from 15 NATO member
states and its Partnership for Peace Program also discussed how to
strengthen political dialogue between NATO and Partnership for
Peace states.
</P>
<P>
Russian ambassador to NATO Vitalij Curkin reiterated Russia's
opposition against NATO's eastward expansion. He said European
security would be less assured after NATO's enlargement.
</P>
<P>
Romanian President Emil Constantinescu again expressed his wish
that Romania should be in the first of the new group to join NATO.
</P>
<P>
Romania would be very disappointed if it failed to participate
in NATO in its first wave of eastward expansion, he said.
</P>
<P>
United States Under Secretary of Defense John White said his
country firmly supports the entry of the Czech Republic, Poland
and Hungary into NATO in the first wave of the alliance expansion
as the three nations were qualified to join the military
alliance. 
</P>
</TEXT>
