<HEADLINE> NATO Begins Science Program For Eastern Europe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LISBON, June 25 (Xinhua) -- The scientific committee of the
North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO) introduced a "Science
for Peace" program today, which aims to help the integration of
East European countries into NATO's scientific projects.
</P>
<P>
At the meeting in Cascais, near Lisbon, Portuguese Science and
Technology Minister Mariano Gago said the program will foster
scientific development in those countries and promote world
stability within a climate of dialogue and cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Ten years ago, NATO's scientific committee undertook the
"Science for Stability" program directed at financing research
programs in Portugal, Greece and Turkey, and narrowing scientific
and technological gaps between these countries and more developed
members of the bloc.
</P>
<P>
Thanks to the program, hundreds of Portuguese researchers were
provided with scholarships for doctorate studies.
</P>
<P>
Science for Peace and Science for Stability programs are
designed only for research for peaceful purposes.
</P>
<P>
Jean-marie Cadiou, NATO's assistant secretary general, attended
the meeting, which will end on Friday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
