<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cable Across "Roof of World" to Be Constructed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 26 (Xinhua) -- China has started construction of
a 2,754-kilometer fiber optic cable across "roof of the world",
the Qinghai-Tibet Plateau.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Posts and Telecommunications (MPT) announced
here Wednesday that the cable will link Lanzhou, capital of
northwest China's Gansu Province, with Xining of Qinghai Province
and Lhasa of Tibet Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
Construction of the cable system has started in Qinghai
Wednesday, and it will become operational in December 1998,
costing 610 million yuan (73.5 million US dollars).
</P>
<P>
"The cable system will be the world's most difficult fiber
optical project in terms of construction condition," said a report
in today's "China Daily".
</P>
<P>
About 840 km of the cable will be 4,500 meters above sea level
or even higher, where oxygen in the air is 50 percent less than
places like Beijing.
</P>
<P>
Construction will only be possible there from late spring to
early September, when windstorms and snowstorms are not frequent.
</P>
<P>
A MPT official said after completion, the cable system is
expected to provide 21,330 long-distance telecom circuits and
therefore greatly help improve the telecommunication capacities of
northwest and southwest China and Tibet in particular, a big boost
to local economic development.
</P>
<P>
Tibet is the only province-level region without
cross-provincial fiber optic cable links. This cable system is
part of plans to aid Tibet launched by the central government for
the coming few years.
</P>
<P>
The Lanzhou-Xining-Lhasa cable system is one of 23 major fiber
optical cables which MPT plans to build by the year 2000. These 23
cables will connect all Chinese provincial capitals and major
cities and greatly upgrade China's telecommunications capacities
when completed.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
