<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bailey Wins Again in Paris Grand Prix </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, June 25 (Xinhua) -- The Canadian world and Olympic
champion Donovan Bailey once again stamped superiority on the
international sprinting arena by scoring a commanding victory in
the 100 meters at the Paris Grand Prix on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Bailey brushed aside the drizzle and wicked conditions to win
the dash in 10.07 seconds, Americans Tim Montgomery and Brian
Lewis came second and third in 10.12 and 10.19 seconds
respectively.
</P>
<P>
However, the man who set up a 150-meter showdown with the
Canadian on June 1 for the fastest-man-in-the-world title suffered
a humiliation.
</P>
<P>
Michael Johnson crashed to his first 400 meters defeat for
eight years when the world and Olympic 200m and 400m champion
could only finished fifth in 45.76. Fellow American Antonio
Pettigrew won the race in a time of 44.86 seconds in damp weather.
</P>
<P>
Another disappoinment was local favourite Marie-Jose Perec.
The women's 200 and 400 meters Olympic champion dampened her fans'
heart by coming in a poor seventh in 200m race which was took by
Inger Miller of the United States in a time of 22.48 seconds.
</P>
<P>
In other performances worth mentioning, Namibia's Frankie
Fredericks, second to Johnson and Bailey respectively in the
Olympic 100 and 200 meters, took the 200 easily by 20.38, while
in-form American Bryan Bronson postered 48.15 to win the 400
meters hurdles.
</P>
<P>
The constant drizzle made world record attempts very
difficult. Ethiopia's Haile Gebrselassie ran well short of his own
5,000 mark when he clocked 13 minutes 1.51 seconds.
</P>
<P>
Moroccan Hicham El Guerrouj beat his Algerian rival Nourredine
Morceli in a stirring 1,500 meters, winning three minutes 31.87
seconds.
</P>
<P>
Kenyan Denmark-born 800m Olympic champion Wilson Kipketer
confirmed his already authorized territory by taking the title
with 1.44.03. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
