<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egyptian Defender Banned for Life </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 25 (Xinhua) -- Defender Ibrahim Hassan has been
banned for life from Egypt's national team and suspended for a
year from domestic competition for making obscene gestures at
Moroccan fans during last weekend's African Cup qualifier.
</P>
<P>
The punishment was ordered by the Egyptian Football Federation.
</P>
<P>
Hassan, 30, was the veteran of Egypt's 1990 World Cup
campaign. He had already been suspended for six months by his
Cairo club al-Ahli and fined 10,000 pounds (3,000 US dollars).
</P>
<P>
Hassan made the obscene gesture at Moroccan fans after Egypt
conceded a second-half goal to Morocco on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The loss dropped Egypt to 0-3-1 and third place in qualifying
Group Three with three points, five behind group leaders Morocco
and Senegal with only two matches to play.
</P>
<P>
Only the top two teams in each group advance to next J in
Burkina Faso.
</P>
<P>
Egypt already has been eliminated from qualifying for the 1998
World Cup. 
</P>
</TEXT>
