<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> North Urged to Change Pattern of Consumption </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Speaking at the 19th special session of the General
Assembly, Venezuelan Environment Minister Rafael Martinez-Monro
said that patterns of of production and consumption in developed
countries must change.
</P>
<P>
A quarter of the world's population consumed 75 percent of
its resources and produced 95 percent of its waste. The link
between population and development must be profoundly
recognized. The current special session of the assembly should
adopt an ambitious and broad-ranging plan of action, but that
plan should be backed up by serious international cooperation,
he stressed.
</P>
<P>
Iranian Foreign Minister Ali Akbar Velayati said that rapid
industrialization of the developed countries, coupled with their
unsustainable patterns of consumption, have had an irreversible
destructive impact on the environment.
</P>
<P>
Given their role in environmental degradation in the past two
centuries, and their current access to environmentally sound
technologies and financial resources, developed countries bore
the legal and moral responsibility, he said.
</P>
<P>
Sarwono Kusumaatmadja, Indonesia minister of state for the
environment, noted that unsustainable patterns of production and
consumption in developed countries, together with poverty and
underdevelopment in the developing world, were the predominant
sources of environmental degradation.
</P>
<P>
Representatives from small island countries also urged the
international community to curb the emission of carbon dioxide
and pace of climate change. Otherwise, they would be hit by more
unbearable natural disasters. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970626.0288 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Albright Starts Southeast Asia Visit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 25 (Xinhua) -- Madeleine Albright left for
Hanoi today in her first trip to Southeast Asia since she became
the U.S. secretary of state this year.
</P>
<P>
"She's going to work on the relationship, try to advance our
relations with one of the more important countries in Southeast
Asia," State Department spokesman Nicholas Burns told reporters.
</P>
<P>
Albright will explore progress in accounting for U.S.
servicemen missing in the Vietnam War, a key issue in bilateral
ties, Burns said.
</P>
<P>
U.S. and Vietnamese authorities are trying to account for more
than 1,500 U.S. servicemen listed as missing in action during the
Vietnam War, which ended in 1975.
</P>
<P>
The secretary of state will also discuss economic relations and
broader political issues when she meets Vietnamese officials,
Burns added.
</P>
<P>
After her visit to Vietnam, Albright will go on to Cambodia
according to the original schedule, but officials here have
indicated this looks less likely than before because of security
concerns.
</P>
<P>
If she cancels the Cambodia trip, Albright still has a chance
for a visit in late July when she attends an Association of
Southeast Asian Nations meeting in Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
Albright's last leg of her trip will be Hong Kong, where she
will attend a ceremony on July 1 for the return of the city to
China after more than 150 years of colonial rule by Britain.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
