<DOCNO> XIE19970626.0289 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philips Announces Audio CD Recorder </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, June 25 (Xinhua) -- The Dutch electronics company
Philips today announced the development of a new CD audio recorder
that will allow consumers to create their own CDs.
</P>
<P>
Philips said in a press release that the CD-recorder will plug
easily into any existing home audio system and allows users to
record from all analogue or digital audio sources.
</P>
<P>
The new recorder offers consumers the ability to create and
play CD-quality recordings and is fully compatible with the
existing Audio CD format.
</P>
<P>
Philips said that its new CD-recorder will include various
agreements made worldwide on copy protections like SCMS, the
Serial Copy Management System.
</P>
<P>
"The ability to make your own Audio CDs has been something of a
Holy Grail among consumers," said Doug Dunn, chairman and CEO of
Philips Sound &AMP; Vision.
</P>
<P>
"Now consumers can easily create their own recordings, with the
quality and convenience of a Compact Disc. The recordings made by
consumers can be played back on the CD equipment they already own
for home, portable and in-car use. The present installed base of
CD Audio player already exceeds 500 million worldwide," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Philips CD-Recorder is currently the only audio recorder
which is compatible with both CD-Recordable and CD-ReWritable
media.
</P>
<P>
CD-Recordable discs can be "written once," meaning that a disc
can be created only once. These discs can then be player on any CD
Audio player.
</P>
<P>
CD-ReWritable discs can be "written and rewritten," meaning
that tracks can be erased and re-recorded as needed, several
hundred times. These CD-ReWritable discs will not play on existing
CD-Audio players.
</P>
<P>
Philips said that it will make its future CD Audio players
compatible with CD-ReWritable discs starting in 1998.
</P>
<P>
It also announced that the introduction of the CD-Recorder will
be towards the end of 1997 and the beginning of 1998 in Europe for
an estimated street price of 1,500 Dutch florin (some 773 U.S.
dollars). Other regions will follow shortly, it said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
