<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German Economy Shows Signs of Improvement: Institutes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, June 25 (Xinhua) -- Two of Germany's leading economic
research institutes said today that they have seen some signs of
improvement for the German economy.
</P>
<P>
The IFO Institute for Economic Studies in Munich said in its
latest economic report that economic prospects had improved
slightly, with the outlook in eastern Germany clearly getting
better, the German news agency DPA reported today.
</P>
<P>
According to IFO, the automotive and electronics industries in
western Germany were benefiting from an upswing in demand. But the
machinery sector was less than satisfied.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Institute for World Economy in Kiel said in its
report issued today that the German economy was experiencing a
widespread upswing and export prospects remained favorable.
</P>
<P>
It also predicted a turnaround in the job market in the second
half of 1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
